<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopia Celebrates 14th Anniversary of Marxist Revolutiuon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON> marked the 14th anniversary of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s Marxist revolution Monday with a brief address devoted to the nation's longstanding civil war in the north. Government troops and civilians mobilized since the conflict intensified in March are `` presently engaged in a bitter fight,'' <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> told the thousands of people packed into the capital's downtown Revolution Square His forces claim to have repulsed insurgencies in its northernmost province, <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>'s southern neighbor, <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> says it has retaken all major cities and towns since the rebels overran the region in April and May. No major engagements have been reported with the separatist <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> since the government in May said its forces had foiled rebel attempts to take the strategic city of <LOCATION> Keren </LOCATION>, 56 miles northwest of the provincial capital of <LOCATION> Asmara </LOCATION>. However, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said the rebels were sabotaging and endangering the lives of all citizens and hampering the development of public and private institutiones. The task ahead `` is clearly an arduous one,'' he said in his 20-minute address. The Eritrean guerrillas have been fighting a separatist battle for 27 years in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s longest civil war. In <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Tigray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> took up arms 14 years ago demanding greater autohomy for their region. <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> inherited the insurgencies when he and a clique of military men dethroned <LOCATION> Emperor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Selassie </LOCATION> in 1974 and replaced the emperor's 44-year feudal reign with a Marxist government. One day before last year's anniversary of the revolution, the provisional military government which had ruled since the revolution was replaced by a <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> which has a popularly elected legislature. However, power still sits with <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> who has ruled <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> since Feb. 12, 1977. In his speech, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> also referred to <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s unusually good rains this year and expressed confidence that if the wet weather continues, the nation `` will, in a short time, be free of food shortages which have made us the butt of an unhealthy comment.'' The Horn of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> nation suffers chronic droughts which in 1984-85 led to a famine that killed an estimated 1 million people and sparked the largest international relief effort in history. Rains failed again in 1987 causing widespread crop failures that threatened an estimated 3.2 million people with starvation in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
