<HEAD>Union Leaders Call Off 13-Day-Old Mail Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Union leaders ended <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 13-day mail strike Monday, but home and international service will remain disrupted for two weeks as workers wade through a backlog of 150 million letters and packages, officials said. The national executive board of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 180,000 <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> employees, announced its support Monday for a pact to end the walkout, said spokesman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Slater </PERSON>. `` The objective by both sides should be to return to work by Thursday,'' <PERSON> Slater </PERSON> said. The 100,000 striking workers will iron out return-to-work details with managers at local post offices, he said. `` This has been an extremely damaging dispute for our customers,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cockburn </PERSON>, managing director of <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letters </ORGANIZATION>, the letters and parcels division of the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. `` There is a mountain of mail, and there will be an all-out effort to move it.'' Union Secretary-General <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON> said local union chiefs will forge their own deals on overtime and the use of temporary workers. `` We are going to try to get this industry back on its feet with the cooperation of the workforce,'' he said in a TV news broadcast on Channel Four. <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> leaders agreed to a back-to-work plan last Thursday, but <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON> said he wanted `` no misunderstanding'' and sent his negotiators back to the table over the weekend. Monday's agreement also establishes a framework for further discussions on the strike's central issue of regional pay supplements. <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Corfield </PERSON> said local managers may press returning strikers to accept a number of temporary employees to cope with the `` Christmas-like'' volume of mail. International mail, first-class letters and parcels will receive priority as the backlog is cleared, said Ms. <PERSON> Corfield </PERSON>. Public mailboxes, which have been sealed throughout the dispute, will reopen `` only when we can guarantee people normal service again,'' she said. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> wishes to pay bonuses to new workers in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, where the cost of living is high and retaining workers proves difficult. The union demanded that the bonuses be paid across the country or not all and began a 24-hour work stoppage Aug. 31 that burgeoned into a series of crippling wildcat strikes. <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON> said a deal could be reached over the pay issue within six weeks. About half of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 1,500 local post offices closed down during the strike and of the 82 major sorting centers, only one, in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, was open for business before the agreement was announced Monday, said Ms. <PERSON> Corfield </PERSON>.
