<SECOND>PM-Frog Legs,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pascagoula Businessman Gears Up For Frog Leg Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A businessman is leaping to fill the gap created by dropping supplies of bullfrogs, whose legs are consumed as a cripsy delicacy in the South. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Maghan </PERSON> was almost hopping in anticipation Monday of an experimental program to raise the big, hopping amphibians. `` It's not really even off the ground yet. But we're pretty excited,'' the owner of <ORGANIZATION> Stillashak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Pascagoula </LOCATION> on the Gulf Coast. `` If you look what has been done in this state for the shrimp, oyster, striped bass and redfish industies, there's no reason it ca n't be done for frog legs,'' <PERSON> Maghan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Maghan </PERSON> said that three years ago he was paying $ 2.15 to $ 2.20 a pound for frog legs. The price is now about $ 4.06 per pound. `` I have been quoted as much as $ 5 to $ 5.10. That goes to show you that the market is way up. Three years ago, I was getting about six to eight pair of legs to the pound. Now, its about four to six pairs per pound. `` But we are also looking at the remnants of supplies, and those are depleting fast,'' he said. <PERSON> Maghan </PERSON> said in 1986-87, more than 8.6 million pounds of frog legs came into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. He said the market could be as much as 10 million pounds. But <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> have put a five-year moratorium on such exports, he said. `` They -LRB- the bullfrogs -RRB- are wild over there and they have taken so many of them that the insect problem has increased, so they are n't shipping any more. `` But I believe there is no reason why <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> ca n't raise all the frogs we need,'' he said. <PERSON> Maghan </PERSON> said the adult frogs eat insects, but he's trying to come up with a feed that will increase their size and growth. He plans to start with tadpoles and raise them all the way to adults. `` It is a long process,'' <PERSON> Maghan </PERSON> said. `` It is not something we expect to do overnight. We expect to raise the critters in a pond, but everything else is still up in the air.''
</TEXT>
