<HEAD>Jordan to Buy Tornado Jets from The United Kingdom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> has reached an agreement with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to buy an undisclosed number of the multi-role Tornado fighter jets, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Petra </ORGANIZATION> reported. A senior air force official told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Monday that the agreement was formalized during a meeting between King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. He did not say when the meeting took place, but <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> has been in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> for several days on a private visit. The official, who requested anonymity in line with air force regulations, refused to say what the deal was worth or how many planes were involved. <PERSON> Petra </PERSON> also did not give such details. Sources said earlier the king was seeking to buy 40 Tornado warplanes. The agency said the deal was part of the `` the king's desire to develop and strengthen the defense capabilities of the Jordanian air force.'' <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> turned to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> blocked a deal involving the sale of F-20 and F-16 warplanes to the <LOCATION> Jordanian </LOCATION> air force. Last year, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> bought 72 Tornado jets from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> for similar reasons. In February, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> agreed to sell <ORGANIZATION> Jordan </ORGANIZATION> 20 Mirage 2000 fighter jets.
