<HEAD>`Red Barron' of Florida Legislature Ousted After Three Decades</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Among the portraits of former <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> presidents hanging in the chamber, it's easy to pick out <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Barron </PERSON>. He's the one riding the horse. The Panhandle lawyer-rancher, who friends and foes alike call one of the most powerful men in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> government, exercises his authority `` exactly like the Godfather,'' a former colleague says. But that era is coming to an end. The 66-year-old, auburn-haired `` Red Barron'' was narrowly defeated in the Democratic primary on Tuesday. He lost to <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruner </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Walton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> lawyer born a year after <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> was first elected to the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> 32 years ago. A conservative Democrat, <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> served as <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> president in 1975-76, once ordering then-Gov. <PERSON> Reubin </PERSON> <PERSON> Askew </PERSON> to stay out of the upper chamber, although in much more colorful words. Since then, he has served almost continuously as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, giving him control over the legislative calendar and make-or-break authority over bills. `` He's really one of a kind,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, historian and former clerk of the state House. `` I've been here since 1941 and really ca n't think of anybody who compares to him.'' His departure `` will reorganize the thinking in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said. `` The senators no longer will have to puzzle over wat <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> thinks of each bill.'' In his successful primary challenge, <PERSON> Bruner </PERSON> cited <PERSON> Barron </PERSON>'s support of a tax increase and claimed <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> failed to pay attention to constituent needs and was too cozy to state business interests His challenge was aided by feminists angered that <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> helped kill the Equal Rights Amendment and by trial lawyers who opposed <PERSON> Barron </PERSON>'s efforts on behalf of insurance companies, many of them represented by his law firm, to limit the size of verdicts in negligence suits. `` He was the architect of the defeat of the Equal Rights Amendment in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Yard </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION>. `` Good riddance! I think we helped to dig his grave.'' As a result of <PERSON> Barron </PERSON>'s departure, some colleagues have been predicting a more partisan and open <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, and reforms to reduce the virtually dictatorial power of the leadership. <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> exercised his power `` exactly like The Godfather,'' said former Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Roberta </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>. `` His ability to do that was seductive, not in a sexual sense, but he had a truly seductive personality.'' The power was wielded with little regard to party labels and party loyalty. When unable to get his way in Democratic caucuses, he forged coalitions between conservatives in his own party, or `` Dempseycrats,'' and Republicans. He angered Democrat leaders by throwing his support to Republican candidates for national and statewide office, including <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> in his successful run for governor in 1986. Republicans did much of the mourning over his loss. `` I'm shocked, I'm sick,'' said <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a former state <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGAN