<HEAD>Olympic City Is Vibrant Mix Of Old And New Korea</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Frantic growth and modernization rub shoulders with ancient tradition in a constant blur of old and new in this vibrant city, site of the 1988 Olympics. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, home to 10 million people, is the crown jewel in the economic miracle that turned <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> from one of the world's poorest nations into an economic powerhouse in just three decades The city also symbolizes how little some things have changed. Traditional ways of life exist alongside relentless expansion, and slums and poverty mix with prosperous suburbs and wealth. `` <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> is a city of contrasts. One moment you are facing the forefront of the 20th century and then you turn around and see a scene out of the Middle Ages,'' said one foreign resident. Gleaming skyscrapers and hordes of business workers in suits and dresses blanket the commercial districts. But just a few blocks away are tiny, dirty workshops where laborers work at a frantic pace for subsistence wages. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> is ringed with row after row of apartment buildings that house the growing middle classes. The city is also dotted with slums where up to 10 people live in a single room without plumbing. Dazzling new department stores in the center of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> show off the latest fashions and electronic goods. Families dress up to shop and eat hamburgers or pizza at Western restaurants and American fast-food chains. Just a few blocks away is ancient <ORGANIZATION> Namdaemun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> where stall holders hawk their goods to throngs of people packed into the narrow streets. Roadside vendors offer rice, dog meat, squid and other foods that have been staples for centuries. But modern values and habits appear to be prevailing. Nearly everyone dresses in Western clothing and some mothers complain that their children prefer hamburgers to rice. Divorce rates are climbing and dating has become commonplace. Families save to buy cars and appliances for increasingly Western lifestyles. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, devastated during the Korean War in the early 1950s and largely rebuilt, has few ancient or traditional Korean buildings. The pace in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> often is frantic. Workers routinely put in 10-hour shifts and work half days on Saturdays. Office workers stay at their desks to avoid being the first to leave at the end of the day. Children are inculcated with traditional Confucian values to revere their elders, obey orders and work hard. `` We want foreigners to see how much our country has attained. We are proud our country has done so well,'' said businessman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong-ik </PERSON>. But older Koreans say the younger generation is not so mindful of the need to work and take weeklong vacations and other unheard of indulgences. `` These young Koreans are very different. They want everything and do n't listen to their elders,'' said a senior journalist who spoke on condition of anonymity. Many things have been neglected in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> to concentrate on expanding the economy as quickly as possible. Pollution has been allowed to go largely unchecked so business can flourish. The city has few parks or other recreational facilities. `` We need more time to become one of the developed countries. We are still developing,'' said businessman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. South Koreans hope the Olympics will cement its prosperity and modernization. They say there will be more time and money to fix problems that have been neglected. `` <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> can go worldwide through the Olympics,'' said <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chul-yong </PERSON>, a shopkeeper. The Olympics are portrayed as a national mission, and ordinary people talk seriously about their duty to help ensure the Games are a success. The Olympics have spread into almost every aspect of life. The symbol of the Olympic movement _ five interlocked circles _ is stamped on everything from milk cartons and television logos to each <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> subway car. `` The No. 1 Games. The No. 1 people,'' proclaim the subway signs.
</TEXT>
