<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Firefighters took advantage of chilly, damp weather Monday to strengthen lines around fires that have ravaged nearly 1 million acres inside the park, but hot, dry weather was predicted by midweek. `` It's a sleeping giant now,'' <PERSON> Denny </PERSON> <PERSON> Bungarz </PERSON>, a fire incident commander, said during a briefing Monday. `` We want to tie it down so when it wakes up it ca n't run on us.'' Fire activity was limited Monday after a weekend of showers and light snow _ the first significant precipitation since spring _ that gave firefighters a needed break from high wind and temperatures that let fires grow by thousands of acres per day last week. The fires inside the 2.2-million-acre park had burned 939,270 acres as of Monday. Temperatures remained in the 40s in the park Monday, keeping humidity levels at up to 50 percent, but the weather was expected to begin clearing Tuesday and temperatures were to reach 70 degrees by Wednesday, drying the area once again. The cool, wet weekend also helped firefighters in surrounding areas of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, and in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, where a 15,700-acre fire was declared under control Monday. `` We're more optimistic this morning than we have been for some weeks,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Baden </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> director at the <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. `` With the moisture we have on the fires now it's cooled them down to where we can in and work them directly.'' The center, which coordinates forest fire suppression, calls this the worst forest fire season in 30 years. Forests and brush also burned in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, where a 400-acre fire that apparently began from an illegal campfire in an alpine area of Olympic National Park had crews from three states fighting it. And a fire in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s Gold Rush country in the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> forced most of the 4,500 residents of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wildwood </LOCATION> to evacuate for a second time Monday. In <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, a fast-moving fire broke out in dry grass and timber in the <ORGANIZATION> Willamette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> and sheriff's deputies warned residents about six miles southeast of <LOCATION> Oakridge </LOCATION> to be ready to evacuate. The fire quickly burned 1,000 acres in rolling hills 10 to 15 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Oakridge </LOCATION>, forest spokeswoman <PERSON> Lorette </PERSON> <PERSON> Laferriere </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> said there 28 fires still out of control in the West that had charred 1.8 million acres. The favorable weather allowed <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> officials to open all roads through the park Monday except its northeastern entrance leading to <LOCATION> Cooke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, the route inside the park from <LOCATION> Mammoth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hot </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> to Canyon and Tower, and <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Pass </PERSON>. About 1,000 Marines from <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pendleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, were to reach <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday and Thursday to help firefighters, while some of the first soldiers sent to <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, were not to be released until at least Saturday. `` We'll have lots of people here, so maybe we can nail this thing,'' <PERSON> Bungarz </PERSON> said. Although moisture helped slow the advance of the flames, with little growth recorded during the weekend, it would probably dry out quickly, <PERSON> Bungarz </PERSON> said. He added, however, none of the fires would make major progress until the area is thoroughly dried. `` We'd have to have a heck of a lot of rain to put the fire out,'' said fire information officer <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Payne </PERSON> on the 31,500-acre Red Bench fire at Glacier National Park in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. `` You're talking numbers of inches of rain. Despite the return of warmer weather, the arrival of autumn weather with lower temperatures and shorter days had officials optimistic the fires would no longer make major advances. `` We still expect fire activity, but it wo n't be as intense or as much or as fast as it has been in the past,'' said fire information officer <PERSON> Sonya </PERSON> <PERSON> Capek </PERSON>. `` The days are getting shorter, so the burning period is getting shorter.'' North of the park in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, Gov. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwinden </PERSON> canceled his sweeping ban on all recreational activities in the state's fire-ravaged countryside because of the weekend weather About 1,000 firefighters got the day off Monday in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> because up to a foot of snow fell on the eastern half of the 247,000-acre <LOCATION> Cnyon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> fire north of <PERSON> Helena </PERSON>, said fire information officer <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>. They were taken to a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> facility to warm up and dry out their clothes. More than 100 residents evacuated from scattered homes, cabins and ranches along the fire's eastern front were returning to the region by Sunday and Monday, she added. Also in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Hellroaring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> fire that had charred 81,900 acres and moved into <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> was contained Sunday, said information officer <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Comstock </PERSON>.
