<DATELINE>VADUZ, Liechtenstein (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Smyslovsky </PERSON>, an anti-communist former Russian general whose World War II unit fought with <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s troops against the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, has died at age 91 Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Smyslovsky </PERSON>, who then called himself <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmston </PERSON>, led a 6,000-man contingent known as the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Russian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> of the German Wehrmacht. At the end of World War II, he and 500 remaining soldiers managed to reach neutral <LOCATION> Liechtenstein </LOCATION>, where staunchly anti-communist Prince <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> granted them political asylum. Death notices published in <LOCATION> Liechtenstein </LOCATION> newspapers said he died in the capital <LOCATION> Vaduz </LOCATION> last Monday and was buried Thursday. The mass-circulation Swiss newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sonntagsblick </ORGANIZATION> reported his death Sunday. Once an officer in the Russian Imperial Guards, <PERSON> Smyslosvky </PERSON> went into Polish and German exile after fighting the <ORGANIZATION> Bolsheviks </ORGANIZATION> in the civil war. After <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> invaded <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> in 1941, he became the first Russian to command a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> unit fighting for the Germans on the eastern front. In a 1985 interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, he said his goal was to end communism in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and get rid of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. But he said he was not a Nazi. `` I thought that the Germans would be the only ones who could defeat the Soviets and that the Allies then would defeat the exhausted Germans,'' he said. `` What the Germans did was horrible. <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> corrupted their souls,'' he said. `` But the Soviets destroyed a whole nation, <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Smyslovsky </PERSON> said volunteers from among Soviet prisoners of war formed the bulk of his army, with the rest made up of prewar exiles like himself. When the eastern front collapsed, the unit fled westward and was decimated by fighting. But <PERSON> Smyslovsky </PERSON> and his men, still heavily armed, marched through <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and crossed into <LOCATION> Liechtenstein </LOCATION> on May 3, 1945. Among them was <PERSON> Grand </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Cyrillovich </PERSON>, heir to the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> throne, whom the soldiers had picked up in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. The group encountered no resistance from <LOCATION> Swiss </LOCATION> border patrols guarding the tiny principality between <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, which dissolved its army in 1868. The Russians were disarmed and granted political asylum. A Soviet repatriation commission later interviewed <PERSON> Smyslovsky </PERSON>'s men, and almost half of them agreed to return `` We have never heard from them again,'' <PERSON> Smyslovsky </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>. Most of the rest went into exile in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, including <PERSON> Smyslovsky </PERSON>. But in 1975, he returned to <LOCATION> Liechtenstein </LOCATION> with his wife <PERSON> Irene </PERSON>, who survives him.
</TEXT>
