<DATELINE>DAVAO CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six men firing submachine guns killed a British executive in an ambush about 12 miles southwest of this <LOCATION> Mindanao </LOCATION> island city, police said Sunday. Investigator <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuertes </PERSON> said the victim, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tree </PERSON>, 56, was aboard a service vehicle that left a cocoa plantation when six gunmen opened fire about noon Saturday. Tree died instantly. His Filipino driver suffered only slight injuries, <PERSON> Fuertes </PERSON> said. Tree was vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a Malaysian-Filipino firm. Police initially reported the firm was Swiss-American. Communist rebels near <LOCATION> Davao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> have threatened attacks on American interests. But no such warning has been issued to British businessmen. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> <PERSON> Calida </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Davao </LOCATION> area police commander, said by telephone that the gunmen may have intended to kill the Filipino plantation manager for <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION>. The Filipino manager had refused demands to pay `` revolutionary taxes'' to the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and had been receiving death threats, <PERSON> Calida </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Calida </PERSON> added that the manager, <PERSON> Dioniso </PERSON> <PERSON> Capusan </PERSON>, was supposed to have driven down the same road at the time of the noon attack. <PERSON> Calida </PERSON> said he did not know if Tree had received similar threats. Supporters of <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> meanwhile celebrated the ousted president's 71st birthday Sunday with a rally in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> and a giant birthday cake in <LOCATION> Laoag </LOCATION>, a northern provincial capital about 250 miles to the north. About 5,000 <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> supporters cheered under a light rain as <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' niece, <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocka </PERSON>, blew out the largest of 71 candles on the 30-feet-by-75-feet cake, baked by dozens of volunteers. `` I thank you for having made by brother's birthday as great as this,'' said <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' sister, <PERSON> Fortuna </PERSON> <PERSON> Barba </PERSON>, as she was presented the first piece. Organizers of the cake project hoped about 24,000 people would turn out for the celebration, but police estimated the crowd at about 5,000. In <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, about 3,000 <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> supporters marked their leader's birthday with fireworks and a rally in a downtown square, where speakers denounced President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, who toppled <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> during a popular uprising in February 1986 <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> greeted his supporters in a telephone interview broadcast over <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> radio station <ORGANIZATION> DZEC </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, where he fled after the uprising. `` By the grace of the Almighty, we are still alive and it is my hope that I can go back there, I can come back to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> told his followers. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has refused to allow <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return, citing national security. But the ousted president has asked the anti-corruption court to order his return to defend himself during a court hearing set for November. A decision by the court is pending. If the tribunal orders <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> home, the government is expected to appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' late mother, <PERSON> Josefa </PERSON> <PERSON> Edralin-Marcos </PERSON>, still lies in state. She died in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> last May 4 but remains unburied, and <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> supporters say the funeral will be delayed until Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> allows the former president to come home for the service.
