<FIRST>r p PM-Candidates-Press-1stAdd     09-12 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Candidates-Press - 1st Add,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: and reporting.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Q. What sort of individual do you see putting in the job of White House spokesperson? How much access would the spokesman have to administration thinking and information? Do you condone <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>' practice of manufacturing quotes? A. The job of White House press secretary is one of the toughest in any administration and a number of qualities are important. A press secretary must be honest, ethical, steady, candid with both the media and the president and experienced, with an understanding of the media and its needs. A sense of humor does n't hurt either. If access is important to reporters, it is absolutely vital to a press secretary. ... I understand that to function effectively a press secretary must have a first-hand knowledge of a President's policies and positions ... Finally, on the third question: no. Q. How much access do you believe reporters ought to have to the White House staff? How free would your staff be to talk on the record to reporters? A. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> Administration will be an open one. That does n't mean every staff member will be authorized to serve as an administration spokesman or interpreter of events and policies The best interests of the government, media and public are n't observed by the confusion and misinformation that usually results from that kind of policy. Not in every instance but in most, if something ca n't be said on the record, it's probably better left unsaid. ... Q. What would be your policy on allowing media coverage of military actions -LRB- a la <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> -RRB-? Do you support the pool approach worked out and used in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> exercises, or do you believe reporters and photographers ought to have even freer access to military operations? A. Certainly, the public has a right to know the details of military operations in an appropriate time frame and in a way that does not risk national security. The current relationship between the military and the press is workable and I support it. But that safety of the troops and the success of the mission must be paramount, and I will risk neither.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MICHAEL DUKAKIS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Freedom of Information: For the past eight years, the Reagan-Bush administration has waged an assault on the Freedom of Information Act -LRB- FOIA -RRB- with every weapon in its arsenal _ executive orders, budget cuts, fee guidelines and legislative proposals. Their objective is clear: to gut a statute whose fundamental premise is that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens have the right to know about the activities of their own government. The current administration claims that complying with the <ORGANIZATION> FOIA </ORGANIZATION> is too time-consuming, too expensive and too bothersome. These are excuses for government secrecy. And they could serve as a cloak for incompetence, mismanagement, illegality or corruption. ... As president, I will implement the <ORGANIZATION> FOIA </ORGANIZATION> in the spirit which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended. From <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to Watergate to Iran-Contra, we Americans have learned what happens when government operates in secrecy, accountable to no one. A <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration will treat requesters of information as clients, not as burdens. For only in an atmosphere of the fullest possible disclosure can the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people retain confidence in their government. Relations with the press: Throughout my public career I've believed in a free press and my record shows I've practiced that belief As governor for nearly 10 years, I have been accessible to <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> reporters several times a week. I enjoy the spirited give and take of news conferences and the vigorous exchange of an interview. More important, I understand and appreciate the role of the news media in a free society as laid out two centuries ago in the Bill of Rights to the Constitution. As president, I would hope to continue this pattern of accessibility to the White House press corps, giving them and me the opportunity to utilize our First Amendment freedoms.
</TEXT>
