<HEAD>Campaign '88: Bush, Dukakis Take Opposite Stands on Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When it comes to abortion, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> agree on one thing: each man says he personally does not favor the controversial procedure. But beyond their personal feelings, the Republican and Democratic presidential nominees have staked out opposite stands on whether abortion should be legal and whether the government should pay for the operation for poor women. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> favors a constitutional amendment to overturn the 1973 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision, <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, that legalized abortion. He favors outlawing all abortions except in cases of rape, incest or to save the life of the mother. He opposes Medicaid funding of abortions for poor women except to save the woman's life. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, as a legislator and governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, has been a resolute supporter of women's legal right to choose abortion, as well as government-funding of the operation for the poor. Anti-abortion pickets are a common sight at rallies for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, just as they hounded the Democrats' ticket of <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> and <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON> in 1984. Prior to becoming <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s running mate in 1980, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> opposed a constitutional amendment to overturn legalized abortion. He once supported federal funding of abortions in cases of rape or incest, as well as to save the mother's life. Asked in 1984 why he changed his position, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> replied: `` There has been _ I have to make a confession _ an evolution in my position. There's been 15 million abortions since 1973, and I do n't take that lightly. While <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has altered his stand on the issue, others in the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> remain pro-choice, including the vice president's campaign co-chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, R-Ill Recently, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said his opposition to abortion is not a stand that he expects everyone in his party has to share. Questioned about <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s position during a campaign stop in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> on Friday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` I have a lot of key supporters who agree with <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> and a lot that agree with me.'' He added: `` Who's going to have a litmus test that everybody has to agree with everybody on every single issue? Asked about the hardline stand against abortion in the Republican platform, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` The platform states the position of the platform but nobody in our party takes a litmus test that says that everybody has to agree on every issue. I expect the Democrats could say the same thing.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has been called `` a pro-abortion zealot'' by Dr. <PERSON> J.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Willke </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The group's legislative director, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, said, `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says he's personally opposed, but he wants to subsidize it on demand.'' He pointed to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' sponsoring of a bill in 1970 to legalize abortion in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, and later, as governor, his vetoes of several bills with restrictions on abortion funding. Facing a strident anti-abortion protest in a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb Tuesday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said: `` While I do n't favor abortion or think it's a good thing, I happen to think that in the last analysis it's up to the woman, in the exercise of her own conscience and religious beliefs, to make that decision. `` We should not brand women as criminals for making that decision. I think that's what most Americans believe, and it's certainly what the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has held,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in his acceptance speech at the Republican National Convention in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> Aug. 18, said, `` Is it right to believe in the sanctity of life and protect the lives of innocent children? My opponent says no _ but I say yes. ... We've got to change from abortion to adoption.'' <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abortion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` There is a stark, stark difference between the two candidates'' and between the two parties' platforms on abortion. The Democrats' terse platform, without mentioning the word abortion, says, `` the right of reproductive choice should be guaranteed regardless of ability to pay.'' The GOP platform contains anti-abortion language in several sections, including a plank that declares: `` the unborn child has a fundamental individual right to life which can not be infringed.'' It endorses both a human life amendment and legislation to extend the 14th Amendment's protections to the unborn. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> has said he, too, personally opposes abortion and does not favor federal funding except in cases of rape, incest or to save the mother's life. But the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abortion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> both agree that <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> has usually voted against restrictions on abortion funding and against constitutional amendments to ban abortion. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was absent July 27 when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 73-19 to allow Medicaid funding of abortions in promptly reported cases of rape or incest. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, on a 216-166 vote Friday, refused to go along with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> move, which would be the first liberalization of Medicaid abortion funding in seven years. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> may take up the issue early this week. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, voted with that <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority July 27. But <ORGANIZATION> NARAL </ORGANIZATION> says he was among `` many anti-choice senators'' who voted for the amendment only as an alternative to accepting even fewer restrictions on Medicaid funding. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is rated highly by the anti-abortion groups and lowly by <ORGANIZATION> NARAL </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> says he generally opposes abortion except to save the mother's life. Activists on both sides agree the next president is likely to make several appointments to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that could sway the tribunal's ruling on abortion. The current court has four justices who generally support the 1973 <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> decision, four who have been critical of it and one _ the newest member, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> _ whose views are not yet clear. `` My biggest concern is the next president's role in appointing at least three <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justices, if not more,'' said <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON>, whose organization helped defeat President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s nomination of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> had criticized <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said, `` On Inauguration Day next January, there'll be three pro-abortion justices over 80 years of age.'' A human life amendment is `` a long ways down the road,'' he said, but if the Democrats capture the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> could appoint a pro-abortion majority for years to come.''
</TEXT>
