<NOTE>Eds: CeCe in 2nd graf is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FILLMORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Firefighters failed in their first attempt to cap a burning oil well Sunday after draining thousands of gallons of oil from storage tanks near the blaze, a spokeswoman said. Another attempt to cap the well was planned for Monday, said <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> fire dispatcher <PERSON> CeCe </PERSON> <PERSON> Grives </PERSON>. An attempt to flood the well with saltwater failed when a crack was found in a pipe on the oil rig, she said. Draining oil from 11 storage tanks in the vicinity of the inferno was a pressing concern soon after the fire began Thursday. Each tank holds about 33,600 gallons, county authorities said. One man was burned and $ 5 million worth of drilling equipment was destroyed when the well ignited at a <ORGANIZATION> Seneca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> oil field in <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Padres </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. The blaze apparently began when a spark from an electric fan ignited fumes, officials said. Oil field worker <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, 24, was in serious but stable condition Sunday evening at <ORGANIZATION> Sherman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oaks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> with burns over 50 percent of his body. Oil rig firefighter <PERSON> Coots </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>, whose Houston-based firm, <ORGANIZATION> Boots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Coots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was called to extinguish the blaze, has said the effort would probably take a week. The fire burned at the southern end of the national forest, which reaches into five <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> counties.
