<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     09-12 0987</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drought-related River Traffic Losses Pegged at $200 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A preliminary review by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> of this summer's barge traffic on drought-reduced rivers shows some of the huge problems that have plagued the movement of grain from inland farm points into export shipping channels. In mid-June, low water levels on the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> rivers began to stall barges at choke points for more than a day. By the end of the month stoppages were a regular occurrence. `` Reduced load size, smaller tows and lengthened transit times have dropped the capacity of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> system by at least 50 percent,'' the report said. `` Difficult navigation and increased travel time add to costs, especially for fuel and labor which normally account for about 35 percent of total operating costs.'' Overall, according to a recent industry study, barge operators could lose as much as $ 200 million this year. The smaller river flow forced gyrations in barge rates, the report said. Even before the drought's full effect, rates were going higher because of greater demand. In the first five months, they averaged nearly a fourth more than in the same January-May period of 1987. In the first two weeks of June, barge rates jumped 4 percent from the end of May. By the end of June, rates had nearly tripled. `` This increase was short-lived,'' the report said. `` In the first week of July, rates fell to about 125 percent above the end of May, and by month's end had returned to pre-drought levels.'' By the first week of August, rates from <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, to export points at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, averaged $ 6.85 per ton, up 12 percent from a year earlier. `` The decline in rates after the first week of July resulted from a sharp reduction in demand for barge service,'' the report said. `` As export volume shrank and producers held stocks in anticipation of higher prices, shipments of grain and soybeans in June fell 16 percent from May, and in July dropped 37 percent from May.'' According to the new outlook report by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the higher transportation costs and reduced capacity sharply boosted prices of corn delivered by barge to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s Gulf ports. Between June 17 and June 23, corn prices rose from $ 3.31 to $ 3.32 per bushel to a range of $ 3.63 to $ 3.66 per bushel, the report said. `` These ports account for about 50 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain exports and receive 70 percent of the grain, chiefly corn, by barge,'' the report said. `` Similar price increases are anticipated in the poultry producing areas of the Southeast. Barges normally carry about a third of the grain shipped to these states.'' Trucks are not an alternative to barges for moving grain, the report said. A fully loaded barge holds 1,500 tons of grain, or about 35 truck loads. A mile-long truck convoy, bumper-to-bumper, would replace fewer than 2 -LCB- barges. `` One day, 1,760 barges were stacked above <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, 287 miles from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>,'' the report said. `` Grain in these barges would have filled a line of trucks 755 miles long.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A forecast by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that the cash receipts of farmers are likely to increase this year despite huge production losses due to drought has put economists to work explaining why. Cash receipts, or the gross from sales of crops and livestock, are expected to rise $ 5 billion to $ 9 billion this year from 1987, says the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. In 1980, another drought year, farm cash receipts climbed nearly $ 8 billion. Since droughts have an impact on production, why do n't cash receipts decline? `` One reason is that the prices of drought-affected commodities tend to increase more than production falls, raising the total value of the crop,'' the agency says in a new outlook report. `` Another reason is that marketing does not drop as much as production because stocks -LRB- inventories -RRB- are sold to make up the harvest shortfall.'' The economists say the demand for farm commodities is inelastic, meaning that a 1 percent decline in production, for example, leads to a price increase greater than 1 percent. `` Some farmers may benefit from the higher prices _ those in areas with adequate rainfall, those who irrigate and those with large unsold stocks of previous years' crops,'' the report said. `` However, higher cash receipts -LRB- nationally -RRB- do not imply that all farmers are better off because of the drought.'' The report added: `` Many farmers will suffer large declines in cash receipts if their individual production falls by much more than prices rise. Farmers in drought-stricken areas without large stocks of unsold crops from previous years have little to fall back on.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Honey bees are famous for pollinating crops, but an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> scientist says the bees do n't work hard enough when it comes to hybrid cotton plants. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Loper </PERSON>, a plant physiologist at the <ORGANIZATION> Carl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hayden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, said there's something about cotton pollen that bees do n't like. `` They will spend 20 minutes meticulously combing the pollen off their bodies before returning to their hives,'' he said. And that's time lost from their `` job'' of pollinating cotton plants Bees are needed to pollinate hybrid strains of cotton by carrying pollen from male to female plants, which produce the hybrid seed. Regular cotton does its own pollinating without the help of bees. The hybrid strains have a potential for boosting cotton yields by as much as 25 percent and producing long fiber for specialty markets, <PERSON> Loper </PERSON> said in a recent report. If only the bees would work harder. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> grow hybrid cotton but rely on hand labor for pollination to produce seeds. Labor costs and import restrictions on foreign cotton seed have put pressure on the honey bee to do the job in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Loper </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
