<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush, Saying Reagan Isn't Scary, Spooked By
`Pig'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the current occupant of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is blessed with `` a great sense of humor if you like jokes and stuff.'' What's more, he's `` not scary.'' That's how the Republican presidential nominee sized up President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> during an impromptu lunch with two fifth graders he plucked at random from a crowd at a downtown rally in <LOCATION> Pekin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Keene </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, both 10, were invited by the vice president to dine with him at the Red Hen Restaurant He ordered a chicken sandwich for himself and hot dogs for his two young lunch partners. Talk turned quickly to sports and politics. `` What's your opinion of the Olympics?'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> asked the two boys. Brent said he hoped to watch the games on television. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he had just been to a sendoff in <LOCATION> Disneyland </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Olympic athletes headed for <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> _ an event he said he enjoyed immensely. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> asked if either one lived on a farm. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said he did, one with horses and cows, and that in fact his mother had just gotten a bad bruise in a riding accident on a `` really crazy horse.'' She was `` very lucky'' the horse did n't fall on top of her, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> observed, recalling the rodeo accident that claimed the life of <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldrige </PERSON> in 1987. Brent then got his question in: `` What's the president like?'' `` He's a good guy, he's got a sense of humor if you like jokes and stuff. He's very, very nice, not scary, a guy you can talk to,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` Some guys you can relax with and some you ca n't,'' he added. But the two fifth graders themselves were anything but relaxed. Not only were they eating lunch with the vice president in front of an imposing troop of photographers and reporters, but so much time had elapsed that they feared being stranded. They had come to town on a school field trip. `` How will you get back?'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> himself wondered. `` I do n't know,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> responded glumly `` Somebody ought to tell them -LRB- the teachers -RRB- that they're here,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told an aide The veep assured the two boys he'd make sure they got home _ even if it meant taking them for a ride in his motorcade. However, classmates had been waiting outside the restaurant _ and gave the pair a hero's welcome.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Another meal, another place. It was <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, the end of a day that began with a campaign appearance at a fish packing plant in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, and the vice president was in a romantic mood as he dined alone with <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>, his wife of 43 years. `` I looked over at her and said, ` Bar, you mean a lot to me.'' To which, the vice president playfully told reporters traveling with him on <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Two, Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> responded: `` May I tell you something?'' `` I said, ` anything.' She said, ` Fish spilled on your red tie.''' `` ` Look, sweetie, 43 years, I'm talking emotion,''' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> quoted himself. `` We're talking family values here,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> continued. `` There was an understanding between us at that very moment that transcended the skeptical look on the waiter's face. It was a special moment there. `` Once in a while you luck into something like that on the campaign trail.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> presided over the sendoff of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Olympic athletes at <LOCATION> Disneyland </LOCATION>, his staff took pains to make sure that the vice president was not standing directly alongside Goofy, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouse </PERSON> or other well-recognizable Disney characters. They did n't want the inevitable photo of such a pairing to fall into the wrong hands. When reporters observed to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that he appeared to be keeping his distance from <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouse </PERSON>, the vice president responded: `` I was only one down from the damn guy.'' However, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that he was rattled by one of the Three Little Pigs. `` He just kept staring at me, with this expression,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, making a funny face. `` My word of honor: I looked over there, and said, It's not the mouse that's bothering me. And he -LRB- the pig -RRB- kept, he kept ... His expression never changed, never changed. Just stared at you all the time.''
