<HEAD>Prison Population Hit Record Total of 604,824 in June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government says federal and state prison population grew to a record 604,824 inmates in June, increasing at a rate that would require 900 new prison beds every week. The federal <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday that the national inmate population grew by 4 percent in the first six months of 1988, with the number of female prisoners increasing by 6.7 percent. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, which added 5,146 inmates for a 7.7 percent increase during the period, accounted for 22 percent of the nationwide growth in the prison population and housed nearly 12 percent of all federal and state prisoners, the report said. The largest percentage increases from Jan. 1 through June 30 occurred in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, which reported 17.9 percent more inmates.
