<HEAD>Unionists: Talks Will Go Nowhere Without Legalization of
Solidarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity advisors say round-table talks with communist authorities may not get off the ground unless the government shows it is willing in principle to reinstate the independent labor movement. On Sunday, a group of intellectuals and artists met with Solidarity chairman <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> to endorse his participation in the talks. The roughly 60 advisors, calling themselves the Council on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, also demanded the immediate legalization of The government promised the talks on jointly solving <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s economic and social crises in exchange for an end to a nearly three-week strike wave and a mediator said Sunday that the discussions could begin this week A resolution adopted by the the advisors said: `` The most important condition for the beginning of a true dialogue between the civil opposition and the authorities -LRB- is -RRB- the legalization of Solidarity and the immediate implementation of pluralism.'' The labor unrest that began in mid-August and ended Sept. 3 posed the most serious threat to the government since it suppressed Solidarity with a 1981 military crackdown. Authorities had promised <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> in talks Aug. 31 that they would discuss legalizing Solidarity if he persuaded workers to end their occupation strikes. `` We are extending our full support in negotiations concerning this issue to the founder of Solidarity,'' Sunday's resolution said, referring to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. No date has been set for the talks with authorities, but <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Stelmachowski </PERSON>, the law professor who has been acting as a mediator in arranging the meetings, said they could begin this week. Union advisers said the talks might not get anywhere unless there is evidence authorities are willing in principle to legalize Solidarity. `` No round-table talks make sense unless at their first stage, or even in the preparatory stage, the authorities' intentions are made credible ... by some form of recognition of Solidarity's right to function legally,'' <PERSON> Piotr </PERSON> <PERSON> Konopka </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> aide, told reporters. Solidarity hopes for some signal on the government's willingness to recognize Solidarity during a preparatory meeting to be held with officials before the round-table talks, several Solidarity advisers said. Sunday's session was part of a two-day Solidarity conference in the northern port of <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>. About 100 people gathered after Sunday Mass in a room at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brygida </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which serves as the headquarters of the Solidarity leadership. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> joined intellectuals, workers and regional Solidarity leaders for the session, chaired by <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>, a historian and one of <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s closest advisers. Included in the group of writers, actors and scholars were filmmaker <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Wajda </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> newspaper editor <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Turowicz </PERSON> and former head of the journalists' union, <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bratkowski </PERSON> A spokesman for the group, author <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Osmanczyk </PERSON>, told reporters during a break in the discussions: `` By means of recognizing pluralism we might finally become a normal state, where a majority of citizens control the ruling minority, like elsewhere in the world.'' At the Mass earlier, the Rev. <PERSON> Henryk </PERSON> <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON> spoke to a congregation of 5,000 Solidarity supporters, stressing the need for unity in Polish society as the talks begin. `` Today there is a chance for round-table -LRB- talks -RRB- and we can not waste it,'' he said in his sermon. `` Just the opposite, we have to break down all the barriers, cast in solid concrete, to get there and sit at that table.'' <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Romaszewski </PERSON>, a Solidarity activist from <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> who monitors human rights abuses in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for the union, said before Sunday's meeting that the mood was optimistic. He said Solidarity was more active and better organized than it has been in years. The union federation was banned the year after martial law was imposed in 1981.
