<HEAD>Floodwaters Drop, But Disease Climbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Problems of distributing relief materials to millions of stricken people and combating the rapid spread of disease plagued this flooded nation today despite steady declines in river levels. President <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> told a news conference his government has been trying to reach an estimated 30 million to 40 million people who were either marooned by the floods or in need of food and medical assistance. The flooding that started June 13 has claimed 866 lives, according to the government. Daily reports by <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> newspapers put the death toll at 1,647. The number of known diarrhea cases in the country continued to rise, with the government's <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> reporting more than 211,000 cases nationwide. However, the pro-government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Bangladesh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> today quoted relief officials as saying the number exceeded 300,000. <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> said 130 people were known to have died of diarrhea. He said he was unaware of any cholera cases, but doctors and newspapers said cholera has been diagnosed in patients who drank flood-contaminated water. About 5 percent of the patients admitted to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diarrheal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> had contracted cholera, according to a doctor who spoke on condition of anonymity. When asked about cholera at his news conference, <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> said, `` I have no reports of cholera, but I will check up.'' Both illnesses have similar symptoms, but cholera is more serious and verified through laboratory tests. The doctor said 550 people suffering from diarrhea or cholera had been admitted to the diarrhea center since Sunday. Last month, the center averaged 155 patients a day. He said the current percentage of cholera cases was normal, even during non-flood periods. `` Cholera is endemic in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>,'' he said. Asked about the possibility of illness escalating as the flood waters receded, <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> said: `` The fear of having an epidemic is already there.'' He noted that his country has only 8,000 doctors. In a country with a population of 110 million, that is a ratio of 13,750 per doctor, compared with one doctor per 5,000 in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and one per 780 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> said estimates indicate 3.5 million tons of grain have been destroyed by the floods _ 20 percent of the grain needed to feed the country this year. <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> said foreign pledges for flood relief have reached about $ 280 million. He said the rebuilding of roads washed away by the floods would require at least that amount. About half the aid offered so far has come from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has pledged nearly $ 150 million in wheat, wheat seeds and cash for emergency airlift assistance as well as contributions to international agencies such as Save the Children, CARE and World Vision Relief and Development. An American C5-A Galaxy trasnport plane arrived in <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> today, carrying water tanks and purification units and plastic sheeting to be used for temporary shelters. The floodwaters have covered three-fourths of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>. `` For centuries the people of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> have lived with floods, but never before have the rivers unleased such fury on her people,'' the president said. The <ORGANIZATION> Flood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> said today that all major rivers were falling but remain above flood level. The Brahmaputra dropped 8 inches at some stations since Sunday. The smaller <LOCATION> Buriganga </LOCATION>, which has flooded about half of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, dropped 2 inches during the same period. `` The flood situation in the country is steadily improving,'' said one control center official, speaking on condition of anonymity. On Sunday, <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> called for water experts from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> to meet to discuss flood-control in the region, which is hit by annual monsoons from June through September. <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> told a gathering in the northern township of <LOCATION> Grudaspur </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> did not have the expertise nor resources to tackle the problem alone.
