<HEAD>President Embarks on Historic Trip Into Black Africa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> embarked today on his first summit-level mission into black <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, flying to Marxist-ruled <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> for talks with a government that has blamed its woes on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. After meeting with President <PERSON> Joaquim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> near a South African-assisted hydroelectric project, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> was to continue on to <LOCATION> Malawi </LOCATION> for talks Tuesday with President <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamuzu </PERSON> <PERSON> Banda </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Malawi </LOCATION> is the only African state maintaining full diplomatic ties with white-ruled <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON> were expected to discuss a mutual non-aggression treaty signed between the two countries in 1984. The treaty lapsed in 1985 when <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> produced evidence that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> violated it by continuing to assist the <ORGANIZATION> Mozambique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> rebel movement, which began an insurgency two years after independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975. The war, combined with drought, has left millions of Mozambicans homeless and short of food. Many Western governments, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, have increased aid to <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> and endorse its contention that the rebels receive covert logistical and communications aid from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> insists it no longer aids the rebels, and <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> is expected to try to convince <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON> to mute the allegations. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, whose plane departed from an air force base at <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, was accompanied by his defense minister, Gen. <PERSON> Magnus </PERSON> <PERSON> Malan </PERSON>, and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON>'s delegation, which left <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION> for the northwestern town of <LOCATION> Songo </LOCATION> early today, included three <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> ministers and two military commanders, according to the Mozambican news agency AIM. In the past year, as part of an effort to improve its regional image, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has expanded its trade mission in <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION> and pursued economic development possibilities in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>. The two countries also have signed an agreement aimed at rehabilitating <PERSON> Cahora </PERSON> <PERSON> Basso </PERSON>, the giant hydroelectric project in the northern, war-torn province of Tete, so that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> can purchase electricity. The rebels repeatedly have sabotaged power lines leading from <LOCATION> Cahora </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basso </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Even when their relations were badly strained, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> maintained extensive ties. Tens of thousands of Mozambicans work as miners and migrant laborers in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>'s electricity is supplied by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, during his 10 years in power, has had few chances to travel in black <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. In 1986, he was one of numerous dignitaries who attended the coronation of <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>'s King <PERSON> Mswati </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, and in 1987 he made a secret visit to South African troops fighting in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. He had hoped to visit <LOCATION> Brazzaville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION>, earlier this year in conjunction with peace talks on <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> allies reportedly threatened to scuttle the talks if he went.
