<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar opened higher in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> today, but fell against many major foreign currencies following reports the West German central bank intervened and sold dollars, dealers said. Gold prices fell as much as $ 11. Traders in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> said they were surprised by the <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>'s intervention, as the dollar had been trading steadily in a narrow range for most of the morning. Traders had said they expected the dollar to remain steady until American trade figures for July are released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Wednesday. Those figures are expected to show a trade deficit of between $ 10 billion and $ 13.5 billion, they said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar edged up 0.47 yen to close at 133.42 after Japanese trade figures for August were released. Dealers said the trade surplus of $ 4.9 billion was lower than many expected. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 133.60 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday: _ 1.8470 West German marks, down from 1.8490 _ 1.5605 Swiss francs, down from 1.5620 _ 6.2785 French francs, down from 6.2865 _ 2.0900 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0835 _ 1,381.00 Italian lire, up from 1,379.50 _ 1.2388 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.6955, little changed Gold prices fell sharply in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> after oil prices fell again. The precious metal opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 421.80 a troy ounce, down $ 5 from the $ 426.80 bid late Friday. At midmorning Monday, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 418. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was quoted at $ 418.00 when the market closed at 6 a.m. EDT for a local holiday, down more than $ 11 from the $ 429.50 bid late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 5.60 to close at a bid $ 419.18. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 6.39 a troy ounce, down from Friday's $ 6.63.
