<HEAD>Ferdinand Marcos Celebrates 71st Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Philippine President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> promised supporters at his 71st birthday party that he would return to his homeland without resorting to violence. `` It is my habit every birthday to ask, ` Who am I? What have I done to be remembered in history?''' the exiled <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> told about 3,500 supporters at a celebration here Sunday. `` Today I am faced with the greatest crisis that has confronted me. God knows who I am. But how will the people know?' `` Am I a scoundrel? A thief of ill-gotten wealth? I am no scoundrel,'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> said, adding that the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> government should allow him to face accusations in person. `` I will go back, I intend to go back, at any price, without violence,'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> said. `` I say face me now, or face the verdict of history.'' Several criminal and civil lawsuits filed by <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' opponents in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> accuse the ousted leader of plundering billions of dollars from his country during his 20-year rule. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> has filed a petition to return to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, but President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has denied his request. Thousands of supporters, many wearing T-shirts or waving placards bearing <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' likeness, yelled `` Bring Home Marcos'' and `` Mabuhay Marcos,'' which in the Philippine language <LOCATION> Tagalog </LOCATION> wishes a long life. <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, dressed in a long, turquoise-colored gown and several pieces of gold and diamond jewelry, addressed the crowd in <LOCATION> Tagalog </LOCATION> but switched to English to say `` the only hidden wealth of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is in his heart and his mind _ enrichment and enlightenment.'' The event _ which was part birthday party, part floor show and part political rally _ was sponsored by the local group `` Friends of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, who has lived in exile here since February 1986, was greeted by cheers and choruses of `` Happy Birthday'' when he and his wife arrived through a back entrance at the <ORGANIZATION> Blaisdell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arena </ORGANIZATION>.
