<HEAD>American Rabbi: Message of Hope for East German Jews On Rosh
Hashana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American Rabbi <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicker </PERSON> says he's bringing a message of hope to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s tiny and isolated Jewish community, but he says he'd like to see the communist government do more for them. <PERSON> Dicker </PERSON> conducted a <LOCATION> Rosh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hashana </LOCATION> service for about 200 Jews Sunday evening, as part of his two-week stay in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> for the high holidays. <PERSON> Rosh </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashana </PERSON> is the Jewish new year. The country's practicing Jews, estimated to number between 450 and 600, have no permanent rabbi `` They -LRB- East German Jews -RRB- are somewhat isolated,'' the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> rabbi told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` I want to give them a feeling they belong to a group. I'm bringing a message of hope.'' While <PERSON> Dicker </PERSON> says he believes that `` things are loosening up,'' there is still more <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> could do for Jews. `` An improvement is possible,'' the 74-year-old rabbi said in the interview in front of the Temple of Peace synagogue, the only synagogue still in use in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. `` There is a recognition on the part of the officials that they can do more than they have done in the past,'' <PERSON> Dicker </PERSON> said when asked about Jewish life in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` Things could be better.'' He did not specify what improvements are needed. While emphasizing that part of his stay would include a `` spirit of criticism,'' he said he did not wish to become embroiled in a political dispute and said he had been well received. He is in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> under an agreement worked out between <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for the high holidays. <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON>, president of the congress, said in July that after years of pressure, there is a `` good chance'' that <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> would agree this fall to pay reparations to Holocaust survivors. An estimated 6 million Jews died during <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s Third Reich, and until now <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has refused to pay reparations. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has agreed to restore a second <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> synagogue that has fallen into disrepair. <PERSON> Dicker </PERSON>, now a research librarian at the Jewish Theological Seminary in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, was born in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and was educated in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> until 1936 when he was forced to flee by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. He served as a chaplain with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in World War II and participated in the liberation of a number of concentration camps, including <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dicker </PERSON> said he would be `` a little sad'' to leave <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s Jews, a majority of them elderly people who survived the Holocaust `` My ambition is great, but my effectiveness will be limited,'' he said, noting that Sunday's service was his first in a communist country. The World Jewish <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is searching for a rabbi to serve in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> on what it calls a `` long-term appointment.'' <PERSON> Dicker </PERSON> said he hopes the congress can find a such a rabbi. However, he added that finding a rabbi would be difficult. `` The person would have to be part of <PERSON> Schiller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Goethe </PERSON>, but also be horrified by <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>.''
