 <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> commuters, who endured hours of delays in their last ride with the railway, enjoyed a much smoother commute today, a railroad spokesman said. This morning's commute went `` perfectly,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Knapton </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Metra </ORGANIZATION>, the Chicago-area commuter rail agency that buys service from C & amp; NW. `` All the trains are running on time,'' <PERSON> Knapton </PERSON> said. Friday's evening rush hour was disrupted by a one-day strike of the 2,600 members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. The strike was ended Friday night by a congressionally imposed settlement, but President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed the bill too late to allow usual train service to resume. The C & amp; NW serves about 41,000 commuters in suburban <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and has freight operations in 10 states. Railroad officials were forced to scramble to put together train crews because about half the <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; NW conductors failed to report for work once <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed the bill. `` We told all our members to go back to work when the president signed the emergency board recommendations'' approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Reppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> UTU </ORGANIZATION> Local 577, which represents 382 Chicago-area brakemen and conductors. Trains began running on schedule Saturday as union members went back to their jobs, officials said.
