<HEAD>China Completes Multi-Candidate Elections of Provincial Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has completed its first multi-candidate elections of provincial leaders, the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The authoritative weekly said the elections, which wound up in August, `` marked a new step forward for democracy'' in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, where formerly there was only one candidate for each seat chosen by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. It said that of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 29 provinces and autonomous regions, the governors of eight and the chairmen of 11 provincial people's congresses were chosen in multi-candidate votes Deputy governors and vice-chairmen in 28 regions faced competition, it said. Under a 1986 law, there should be more than one candidate for provincial-level offices and each candidate must be nominated by at least 10 deputies to the provincial congress, or legislature. Final voting is done by the deputies. Ordinary citizens can vote directly only for officials at the township and county level. The weekly said the number of candidates nominated to the provincial posts was 24 percent greater than the vacant positions. `` With the break from the outmoded convention that a candidate, once nominated, would definitely be elected, the notion that officials can only get promotions but never demotions was pushed aside,'' it said. The report also said the elections, held ever five years, increased from 18 to 26 percent those governors and deputy governors under the age of 50. College graduates increased from 69 percent to 74 percent. In people's congresses, chairmen and vice-chairmen under 60 years rose from 8 percent to 30 percent.
</TEXT>
