<HEAD>Teachers Urged To Boycott School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of a black boycott of the district's 17 public schools urged teachers in the school system to call in sick Monday, but a school official said teacher attendance was normal. The boycott was called to pressure officials to oust school superintendent <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vickers </PERSON> and his assistant, <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweatt </PERSON>, both of whom are white. Protesters say the two are not sensitive to the needs of the mostly black school district. `` From 1869 they've had a white -LRB- superintendent -RRB-,'' said protest leader <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, education chairman of the group, Save Our Children. `` We ask for one black person, and we're racist.'' <PERSON> Vickers </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sweatt </PERSON> have declined to comment on the boycott. `` From what I gathered, it is a normal day for absences on the part of teachers,'' Assistant Superintendent <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Peyton </PERSON> said Monday. Some parents also have been holding their children out of class in protest. For two days last week, almost one-third of the district's students were absent from classes. <PERSON> Peyton </PERSON> said 5,564 students were in attendance Monday. Before the boycott began, attendance was 8,834 in the district's 17 public school Thursday, 5,879 students attended, and 6,082 attended Friday. About 200 people marched Saturday through the downtown area in support of the boycott. Police escorted marchers for about a mile through the downtown as they sang `` We Shall Overcome'' and carried banners calling for the superintendent's ouster.
