<HEAD>Church Hit By Deadly 1963 Bombing Now Finds Membership Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attendance at the <ORGANIZATION> Sixteenth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> has declined dramatically in the 25 years since dynamite killed four black girls, but the pastor says its membership is worldwide in spirit. `` Sixteenth Street is not a local church _ Sept. 15, 1963, made sure of that,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. `` It is in the truest sense the people's church.'' The church, which is marking the 25th anniversary of the bombing this week, nearly filled its 1,500 seats regularly in the 1940s and 1950s and became a rallying point for civil rights demonstrators who filled it in the 1960s. Now, it has about 100 members. The church has suffered common urban church problems such as members moving away from downtown. At Sunday's service, which opened the week's anniversary observance program, the balcony was empty, as were many pews on the main floor, and visitors outnumbered members when asked to stand. `` That did n't look so good, as far as the church itself was concerned,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, a deacon and member of the church for 60 years. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, who plays the clarinet and saxophone, is the lone member of the church orchestra, which once had 20 musicians. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> said the church's role during the civil rights movement, while making it a landmark, did not please all the members. `` We suffered a great deal because we had so many threats coming into the church,'' said <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>. The church was formed in 1873 and the building, designed by a black architect and built by a black contractor, was erected in 1906. The bombing heavily damaged the basement area where the girls were killed but the damage was not as severe elsewhere in the building. A white man, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambliss </PERSON>, was convicted of murder in the explosion. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the media coverage of the 25th anniversary may help bring more people to the church. `` Our hope is that there will be some benefits to the whole community, including members of <ORGANIZATION> Sixteenth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. `` We are hoping that we will get the attendance up,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, chairman of the church's board of trustees and a member since 1965. `` That would help us a lot.''
