<HEAD>NBC Cancels `Main Street'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> has canceled its critically praised but low-rated `` Main Street,'' an afternoon news program for children. `` I made the decision last Wednesday that there was just no way that show could live. It was a decision widely expected. I met with the staff on Friday afternoon,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gartner </PERSON> said Monday. For <ORGANIZATION> Gartner </ORGANIZATION>, a newspaper editor and executive who took over as head of the news division in July, it was a quick introduction to the realities of television programming. `` Sure it's hard,'' he said. `` You'd much rather be meeting with the staff and launching something rather than killing something. But the show did n't have the support of advertisers, did n't have the support of affiliates and did n't have support of the audience. As I told somebody, one out of three would have been nice.'' <ORGANIZATION> Gartner </ORGANIZATION> said he now has `` sort of finished the process'' of layoffs that began after last year's efficiency appraisal. The layoffs have involved approximately 400 news division employees. <ORGANIZATION> Gartner </ORGANIZATION> said the last round of layoffs, effective at year's end, included a `` handful'' of permanent employees, along with 60-70 employees who had been hired on a temporary basis for election coverage. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> is closing its <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> bureau as of the end of the year, dismissing six people there. A producer and office manager will maintain an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, but correspondent <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Molina </PERSON> and bureau chief <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Cullen </PERSON> will be transferred to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> has nine domestic bureaus, including <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. It has offices in three other cities. All three network news divisions have been laying off employees for the past couple of years as new management has taken over and reassessed costs.
