<HEAD>Yellowstone Smoke Affects Sky As Far As East Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Smoke from the forest fires in <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> has drifted as far as the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, turning sunsets a fiery red and even affecting the weather. The setting sun `` had a kind of an eerie appearance,'' said <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, about 1,200 miles east of the fires. The hazy smoke made the sun look like `` a big glowing red ball ... it was a very red color which made it spectacular in that regard.'' The smoke was trapped in an upper atmospheric trough, about 15,000 to 20,000 feet up, and was carried by wind over the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, toward the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and out to sea, said meteorologist <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> of the weather service in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The thin layer of smoke passed over the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> area Sunday, dimming the sun to a reddish-orange and lowering temperatures between 5 and 10 degrees, <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said. `` The only effect we ` re having is it ` s interfering with the radiation of the sun,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armbrust </PERSON>, an air-quality engineer with the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> still had a thin, transparent layer of haze Monday, said weather service meteorologist <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerso