<HEAD>Congress Provides Money For Whooping Cranes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation is on its way to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> providing money to buy the last privately held land on a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> island that is a wintering ground for the world's only surviving flock of whooping cranes that breeds in the wild. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> appropriations bill, passed last week by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, provides $ 5.5 million for the purchase of 5,017 acres at the southern tip of <LOCATION> Matagorda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, officials say. The purchase will be the government's third and final acquisition from the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Nature Conservancy, bringing the federally owned tract on the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> barrier island to 11,502 acres. With the growth of the flock over the past four decades, the whooping cranes have had to search for new wintering grounds away from their traditional winter home on nearby <ORGANIZATION> Aransas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, in charge of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' non-game and endangered species program, said as many as 150 whooping cranes are expected to make the journey this fall from <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Territories </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Last year, 132 cranes wintered around the Aransas refuge, with two others ending up elsewhere in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Another flock of about 20 cranes winters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and summers in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said those cranes have not yet reproduced in the wild. A flock of about 40 is kept in captivity at the Patuxent Wildlife Refuge in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>.
