<HEAD>Argentine Unions Hold 24-hour General Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Schools, public buildings and factories closed Monday across <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> as the 3.5-million-member organized labor movement held a 24-hour strike. The strike, set to end at midnight, was called to protest police actions at an anti-government rally Friday in front of Government House in which 113 people, including 37 policemen, were injured. Government officials said the police moved in Friday to stop fighting between rival union groups. Labor leaders denied that and accused the police of brutality. Monday's strike was the 13th organized by the General Labor Confederation since the elected government of President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> was installed in December 1983, ending nearly eight years of military rule. The union federation had rejected a government request to call off the strike, and <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s centrist administration pledged over the weekend to protect anyone who wanted to work Monday. No violence was reported. Guards were posted at public buildings. Supervisors ran the subways in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> and owners of taxis and inner-city buses were encouraged to take shifts behind the wheel when most drivers failed to show up for work. The General Labor Confederation, backed by the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, organized last Friday's rally and an 8-hour general strike to protest <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s economic policies. Inflation registered 440 percent over the last 12 months, with unemployment and underemployment at a combined 14 percent, near 14-year highs. Real personal incomes have declined for three straight years. The labor federation claims that an anti-inflation plan <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> implemented last month does not allow workers' wages to keep pace with increases in the cost of living.
