<HEAD>Mortar Shells Fired at Parliament Building</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three mortar shells were fired Monday at the parliament building, deepening the crisis caused by the stalemate among Christians, Moslems and leftists in selecting a new president. Hours later, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON> announced that legislators would be summoned to meet Sept. 22 for another attempt to elect a successor to Christian President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>. Police said there were no casualties from three 60mm mortar shells that exploded at 6:45 a.m. around the two-story parliament building, known as <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> <PERSON> Mansour </PERSON>. The building is in the no-man's land between predominantly Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> It was the first attack on Villa Mansour in two years. Police said one shell hit the entrance of <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> <PERSON> Mansour </PERSON> and the other two exploded near army and police checkpoints guarding approaches to the building. They said no group claimed responsibility and they did not know if the attack was linked to the electoral deadlock. Right-wing Christians and Moslem and leftist factions backed by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> quickly blamed the others for the shelling. Legislators had met Aug. 18 in an attempt to elect a successor to <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>, whose six-year term expires Sept. 23, but some Christians boycotted the session and there was not a quorum, meaning the selection could not proceed. Under the constitution, the president can not seek a second consecutive term. The boycotting Christians opposed the main candidate, Syrian-backed former President <PERSON> Suleiman </PERSON> <PERSON> Franjieh </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>. By tradition, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s president is a Christian, the prime minister a Sunni Mos