<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> must focus on preventing pollution instead of concentrating on cleaning up existing problems with an `` end of pipe'' strategy, a report provided Monday recommended. To help carry through such a change, the agency's research budget should be increased by about $ 375 million a year _ roughly doubled _ said a committee of the agency's <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in the report. The study was made available by agency officials Monday after an article about it appeared in The <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>. The committee was responding to a request for advice from <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, who, the report said, `` sensed that <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s immediate regulatory needs were driving its research and development efforts, while longer-term research equally important to achieving <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s overall risk reduction goals was being neglected.'' <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Alm </PERSON>, former deputy administrator of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> and chairman of the high-level advisory committee, said in an interview that <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> was correct. `` The problem <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has is it's spending most of its R & amp; D dollars just putting out legislative fires,'' <PERSON> Alm </PERSON> said, referring to research and development money. `` One of its major problems is to look ahead, to anticipate problems.'' `` Obviously you need technical support for the regulations -LRB- but -RRB- ... that has driven virtually all the long-term research away,'' he said. The report said that in the 1970s, efforts to control automobile, industrial and wastewater pollution using `` federally mandated end-of-pipe controls were sensible, targeted, relatively efficient and reasonably cost effective.'' Though cleanups have been predicated on the notion that `` the polluter pays,'' and those controls will still be important, strategy must change, the report argued. `` For one thing, we are discovering environmental contamination in our homes _ e.g., radon _ and in the statosphere _ e.g., chlorofluorocarbons _ that are not emitted by ` pipes' in the traditional sense,'' the report said. For another thing, end-of-pipe control has too often shifted pollution from one place to another, for example, from water to air for toxic pollutants removed from sewage streams by aeration techniques. `` Whenever possible, environmental protection efforts first should be aimed at minimizing the amount of wastes or pollutants generated. Thus waste reduction at its source _ for example, through product design changes, industrial process changes or material substitution _ should be a primary objective,'' the report said. <PERSON> Alm </PERSON> said he believed many businesses would welcome a vigorous program of `` technology transfer'' led by <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> _ a program to show them how their processes could be changed to generate less waste. `` The private sector has ... an incentive through liability questions,'' <PERSON> Alm </PERSON> said. To help keep the need for long-term research in view, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> should convert the position of assistant administrator for research and development from a presidential appointment to a career job, the report argued. In the 18 years for <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s existence, no one has held the job for more than three years, and `` no leader ... has stayed at the agency long enough to implement a sustained, long-term research strategy,'' it said. Ecological research should get more emphasis, having taken a back seat to research to support regulations aimed at protecting human health, the report said.
