<HEAD>Mayor Says He Won't Run For Fifth Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON>, a leading Hispanic politician who once was considered a potential vice presidential candidate, said Monday he's been in public service long enough and wo n't seek a fifth term. `` It's been work and it's been fun. Mostly, it's been the most engrossing and fulfilling thing I've ever done,'' said <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON>, 41, whose term expires next spring. `` Basically, I've been at it for 14 years _ eight years as mayor and six as council member. That's a long time to go at full throttle,'' he said. `` Our country believes that eight years in a high office should be enough to get a job done. `` Presidents serve eight years. Governors serve eight years. And eight years is a good round number for a mayor, especially this one,'' he said. Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> interviewed <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON> in 1984 about possibly running on his ticket. <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON> also has been mentioned frequently as a possible Cabinet-level appointee. Last year, <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON> said he would not seek a statewide office because he wanted to devote time to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> projects and to his son, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>, who was born with a congenital heart defect and with stomach abnormalities. Earlier this year, <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON>, a former president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION>, turned down an offer to make a keynote address to the Democratic National Convention. <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON>, who has met Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, was approached earlier this year by several <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION>