<SECOND>AM-UN-Africa,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Africa's Economic Plight Worsens, U.N. Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is facing huge debts, lagging food production and a soaring infant mortality rate despite broad economic and social reforms, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief, speaking at the opening of a two-week review of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Africa Recovery Program, gave a grim prognosis for the continent. Among the signs of distress he cited: _ Infant and child mortality rates are rising, and are projected to reach 50 million in the period 1985-2000 In every other world region, infant and child mortality is rapidly decreasing. _ By the year 2010, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s debt will be more than 280 percent of its total export income _ Per capita income on the continent fell 2 percent in 1986 and 2.2 percent in 1987, and today is lower than it was in 1980 _ Agricultural production improved by 3.8 percent in 1986 but only 1.1 percent in 1987, despite agricultural policy reforms <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s report marks the midway point of the 1986-1990 Africa Recovery Program, the result of a special <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> session in May 1986, the first such session to focus on one continent. The program was aimed at helping reverse <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s economic decline, but external problems have blocked substantial progress, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said. He said three key problems are <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s depressed export earnings, the cost of repaying its debt and insufficient financing. `` Every day that passes, the debt burden of African countries becomes even more excruciating,'' said <PERSON> Adebayo </PERSON> <PERSON> Adedeji </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> undersecretary-general. Although <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> paid almost $ 1 billion a year to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> in loan costs in 1986 and 1987, resources fell, exports credit declined and loans from the private sector were minor, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief's report said. <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s debt burden `` has become one of the most important factors constraining recovery and development on the continent, and unless urgent action is taken, the situation will worse,'' said <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s total external debt is estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> at $ 218 billion by the end of 1987, almost triple the continent's export earnings. A slump in commodity prices has further hurt <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s economy. Particulary damaging are the sluggish markets for oil, minerals, cocoa, coffee, and tea. These problems largely canceled out any gain that might have been produced by the `` courageous and commendable'' sacrifices of some African governments, such as adopting steep currency devaluations, cutting budget deficits and an turning over some public sector functions to the private sector. `` In many countries such measures involve social costs and political risks,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> noted. Most African nations have embarked on economic restructuring programs, about 30 percent of them with the backing of the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` Most countries are giving greater priority to channeling resources to agriculture, to improving incentives for farmers, to making provision for food security and to combating drought and decertification,'' the secretary-general said. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> urged <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> nations to continue these restructuring programs, but cautioned them to ensure that `` the most vulnerable groups in society are protected from adverse consequences.'' Donor countries should show their support for these reforms by increasing their aid, he said. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> called on industrialized nations to reduce their agricultural subsidies on products competing with African commodities. `` African efforts to pursue and deepen the reform process can not be sustained indefinitely in the face of an adverse external environment and without increased support from the international community,'' the secretary-general said.
