<HEAD>Iran's Parliament Approves 18 Ministers, Rejects Three</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> approved 18 ministers Monday in a vote of confidence for Prime Minister <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON>'s government, but rejected three, including Revolutionary Guards Minister <PERSON> Mohsen </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafiqdoust </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said The two-day debate exposed the deep divisions in the <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> hierarchy that had largely been masked by the need for unity during the 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The veto on <PERSON> Rafiqdoust </PERSON> underscored the anger over disastrous battlefield defeats suffered by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> before it abruptly accepted a year-old <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> Nations-sponsored cease-fire July 18. These setbacks had been blamed on the Revolutionary Guards. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> began observing a truce Aug. 20 and started U.N.-mediated peace talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> five days later. The parliamentary debate, which <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> announced in July, opened Sunday amid a deepening rift between hardline revolutionaries demanding economic isolationism and tight state control of the economy and rivals, such as House Speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who seek to open up oil-rich <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in the postwar era. Several deputies attacked hardliner <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON>'s economic policies, while radical legislators loyal to the premier defended his administration. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> Radio, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, gave few details of Monday's session But the radio said the 11 ministers of the 21-member Cabinet who were cross-examined by the 270-member Majlis, or parliament, included Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSO