anges in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and that <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> could be among the political casualties. <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> reportedly opposed a truce. He opposes allowing foreign multinationals back into <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to help with the massive task of reconstruction. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> and <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> favor a more moderate course and ending <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s self-imposed isolation. <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> on Monday opened <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s 14th international trade fair, in which 36 countries were participating. Some, like <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, were taking part for the first time since the 1979 Islamic revolution toppled the late, pro-Western <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>. The official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, also monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, said other foreign participants included the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> quoted Commerce Minister <PERSON> Abdulhussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Vahaji </PERSON> as stressing that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> welcomes foreign technological assistance for reconstruction projects and said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> now seeks to expand commercial links with the rest of the world. Some Western analysts have estimated that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s postwar reconstruction could cost $ 40 billion.
