<HEAD>Gorbachev Runs Into Complaints From Crowd</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, in his first public appearance after a six-week vacation, ran into crowds complaining loudly about food shortages and living conditions Monday in the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION>. The evening television news program `` Vremya'' led its evening program with a report on the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader's trip to the city, about 2,000 miles east of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had been out of public view since July 30, when he met with Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Soviet officials said he was on vacation. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> asked for support for his reform policies as residents of <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> pressed close to him and complained about lack of hot water and long lines for meat, sausage and other foods. The clamor was in marked contrast to the usual orderly scenes of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> visits on Soviet TV. Many of the comments and complaints were inaudible. `` The most important thing is that you believe in our politics and in the leadership that is still being formed. It's still being formed at the regional and provincial levels,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. He told the residents he was not interested in blind faith, but in reasoned trust for his policies and the people implementing them. `` We're on the right path, comrades,'' he said. `` No need to get lost. We're on the right path.'' The Soviet leader blamed both local and national officials for failing to develop social services in <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION>, and reiterated that he is committed to providing each Soviet family with a separate apartment by the year 2000. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> on a special <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> plane and met with residents near the airport, and again near the city's central square, where he laid a wreath at a monument to Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> He defended his tolerance of greater debate and criticism in the Soviet press and encouragement of cooperatives outside the state-run economy. One woman complained that cooperatives, owned by the people who run them rather than by the government, charge too much for their services. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> agreed that cooperative prices are high, but told the woman that as more co-ops are formed competition will drive prices down. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has encouraged cooperatives to provide goods and services that are in short supply in the state-run economy. A man complained that under his policy of glasnost, or greater openness, the state-run press is free to attack anyone by name, whether they deserve it or not. The Soviet leader responded, `` We need openness, we need glasnost, but it has to be according to our values, according to socialism and according to people.'' No indication emerged how long <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> would remain in <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION>, the regional center for an area that takes in one-tenth of the entire <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> also is the site of a Soviet radar station that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says is an obstacle to arms control negotiations. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> did not discuss the radar site in comments distributed by the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency and shown on Soviet television.
