<DATELINE>SEMIPALATINSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet observers came to this Central Asian city Monday to prepare for the first <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear test monitored by American experts, a step toward ratifying two long-pending arms treaties. Arms negotiator <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, who heads the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> delegation, said it had been `` a long journey, but an even longer journey in the mind'' to reach the point at which the two superpowers are willing to share some of their most closely guarded technology in the interest of arms control. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> spoke before setting off by bus across the steppe to the Soviet test ground. An American team of up to 40 specialists has worked at the site since April, drilling a hole 2,100 feet into the earth to plant a measuring device the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government calls the most sensitive gauge of nuclear explosions. A test blast, to be detonated Wednesday, is similar to one exploded at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> test site on <LOCATION> Pahute </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, on Aug. 17. The devices are being set off to allow each side use its own testing equipment and compare the results with those of the other side to determine the strength of the blast and the accuracy of the monitoring techniques. The joint experiments are expected to lead to <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ratification of two long-dormant treaties limiting underground nuclear explosions to 150 kilotons, still many times more powerful than the bomb that devasted <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. A kiloton is the equivalent of the explosion of 1,000 tons of TNT. Those pacts _ the Threshold Nuclear Test Ban Treaty of 1974 and a similar accord signed in 1976 to limit peaceful nuclear explosions _ were bypassed by President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, who pressed instead for a comprehensive ban on all nuclear testing. His successor, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, shelved the unratified documents, claiming the Soviets regularly violated their limits without permitting on-site verification. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> unsuccessfully sought for 18 months to cajole the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> into joining a Soviet moratorium on all nuclear tests. It abandoned the effort last February and agreed to go along with joint verification of tests as a step toward its goal of a total ban. `` No one thought even a year ago that what is about to happen could happen,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said Monday. He called the joint verification experiment `` a real triumph of confidence-building'' on both sides. Detailed results of last month's test have not yet been released. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, speaking on condition they not be identified, have expressed considerable satisfaction with the results. Reports have surfaced that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> measuring gear, which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> contends is more accurate than Soviet methods, showed that the American test exceeded the 150-kiloton limit. But officials said Monday they regarded that possibility as `` very, very unlikely,'' noting that even with its much-heralded accuracy the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> measuring device can be 30 percent off.
