the desert tent prison at <LOCATION> Ketziot </LOCATION>, about five miles from the Egyptian border. <PERSON> Bakri </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>'s new Palestinian guard was the first of its kind to be set up in the occupied territories and would be financed by <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION> business people, many of whom suffered break-ins after most city policemen resigned. `` The purpose is to guard markets and businesses because there have been a lot of robberies, costing merchants hundreds of thousands of dollars. We need such a body and it was formed on popular demand,'' <PERSON> Bakri </PERSON> said in an interview. He said the guards would carry knives, clubs and walkie-talkies, but that <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities would not let them carry guns. Uprising leaders have ordered all Palestinians who work for the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> military government in the occupied territories, including police, to quit their jobs. The army reinforced patrols and set up checkpoints on main highways throughout the occupied lands. Troops searched Palestinian cars at roadblocks outside <LOCATION> Jericho </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Kalandia </LOCATION> refugee camp in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. Police spokesman <PERSON> Rafi </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> reported extra troops deployed in Arab areas of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, but said no clashes occurred. In one incident, a Jewish settler fired in the air after his vehicle was stoned in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, but no one was injured, witnesses said. Dozens of supporters of the left-wing Progressive List for Peace, a mixed Arab-Jewish party that holds two seats in the 120-member Israeli parliament, demonstrated outside the northern <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Qalqilya </LOCATION> to protest last week's army raid in which more than 200 <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCAT