<HEAD>Human Rights Leader Says Church Massacre Return To Duvalier Era</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with six claiming participation
in massacre; PICKS up 8th pvs: `This act...' Minor editing
throughout to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> PORT-AU-PRINCE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Six people claimed in a radio broadcast Monday that they took part in a massacre at a Roman Catholic church that left at least five dead and 77 wounded, and warned that the slaughter `` was child's play.'' The five men and one woman later appeared on <PERSON> Tele-Haiti </PERSON>, the country's only private television station. In both broadcasts the six said the bloody attack Sunday was aimed at Rev. <PERSON> Jean-Bertrand </PERSON> <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>, the church pastor and a critic of the military government. One of the men said in the Radio Metropole interview, broadcast Monday evening, that `` the people committed the massacre. `` We were after Father <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>; what you saw yesterday was child's play. In whatever parish <PERSON> Father </PERSON> <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> is accepted, a heap of corpses will attend that Mass,'' the man said. None of the six was identified. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Widmaier </PERSON>, manager of <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropole </ORGANIZATION>, said the group came to the station Monday afternoon and claimed participation in the massacre at the church and the stoning later Sunday of two other radio stations and the headquarters of two opposition leaders. During the television appearance, one of the men said the slaughter at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bosco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> was motivated by an internal struggle between <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> and another priest, but they did not elaborate. Two dozen men with guns and machetes burst into the church during a morning Mass in the La Saline slum and shot, stabbed and slashed terrified parishioners, witnesses said. Witnesses said at least a dozen people were killed. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> escaped unhurt and went into hiding. Doctors at the general hospital of the state university reported five bodies were in the hospital morgue and 77 parishioners were hospitalized. Among those injured were a woman and her infant _ both skewered by the same steel pike while the baby girl was in her mother's womb An operation saved mother and child. <PERSON> Franck </PERSON> <PERSON> Romain </PERSON>, mayor of <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> was `` justly punished.'' But <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, compared it to attacks on civilians that occurred during the rule of dictator <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> `` Papa Doc'' <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> and his son, <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON>. `` This act is unprecedented in our history,'' <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> said. `` Even <PERSON> Papa </PERSON> <PERSON> Doc </PERSON> did not dare do such a thing _ penetrate the holy precincts of a church and, after massacring unarmed worshipers, burn it down.'' Dr. <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Blot </PERSON>, who took part in surgery that saved the baby and mother, told Radio Haiti-Inter the sharpened metal rod penetrated the woman below the heart and wounded the baby. He said 10 others required emergency surgery, one for a bullet wound and nine who were stabbed by skewers, a common homemade weapon in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. The rest suffered from various injuries, having been shot, bludgeoned, trampled or slashed. Witnesses speaking on condition of anonymity said Monday they spotted <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION> city hall employees among the assailants, but did not identify them. Witnesses said police and soldiers watched the attack but did nothing to stop it. <PERSON> Romain </PERSON>, a former army colonel and police chief during the 29-year <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> era, denied the charge. `` If -LRB- city -RRB- employees were involved ... I do n't see how I am concerned ... I am not an anarchist, I am not someone who preaches violence and who sends people out to die as <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> has always done,'' <PERSON> Romain </PERSON> said. `` Father <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> has always preached violence ... He who sows the wind, reaps the storm,'' <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropole </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Romain </PERSON> as saying. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>, one of the most popular figures among the poor masses in this <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> nation, regularly has preached against army atrocities and has led his supporters in street demonstrations. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> has been the target of several assassination attempts since Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> came to power as head of a three-man junta on Feb. 7, 1986, the day <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> fled into exile in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Romain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION> mayor until <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>'s ouster, returned to that office in army-run elections in January and remained after <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> ousted civilian President <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> in a military coup in June. <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> was head of the military under the <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> regime. The mayor was a member of a firing squad in the Nov. 12, 1964, execution of two survivors of `` Young <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>,'' a group of U.S.-based anti-Duvalier activists who invaded the country. <PERSON> Romain </PERSON> personally shot and killed two group members. `` On Sunday, -LRB- the forces of law and order -RRB- stood by ... and let a massacre take place,'' <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> said. The radio reports said police and soldiers looked on from an army compound across the street as 300 assailants stoned the church. A smaller group of men armed with machetes, sticks and guns then entered the church and began attacking worshipers. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> condemned the police behavior. `` In spite of the fact that all of these attacks occurred in close proximity to various police and military installations, no actions were taken by the competent authorites to intervene while the attack were taking place,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>, who lives in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, denounced the incident as the work of <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>'s secret police. `` Brute force is the principal instrument of those who now control the country,'' <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> said from his home in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. `` It is the same killers of the Duvalier time organizing the new terror.''
