<DATELINE>LITTLE SILVER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A controversial program that paid potential dropouts to go to class has been revised this year because of negative attention it generated, school officials said Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> received national attention last year when it began paying problem students $ 5 a day, or $ 25 a week, to attend classes regularly, be punctual, do their homework and behave themselves. `` It was picked up by the media as ` Oh, my God, you're paying kids to go to school,''' said Principal <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Nogueira </PERSON>. He said the concept was viewed as `` almost un-American.'' Critics said the program was unfair because it paid some students to achieve what were minimal requirements for the rest, and violated the ideal of education being an end in itself. Officials denied the students were being paid to study. Instead, they said they were getting `` needs-based'' subsidies for improving their academic performance and changing their behavior. National television crews came to the school, students were interviewed on the radio and newspapers reported on the program. `` There seemed to be a lot of hoopla going on about how we were doing it,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lock </PERSON>, a work placement coordinator at the school who helped draft this year's program. `` The attention being paid to it was taking away from our time rather than being with the young people.'' This year potential dropouts will be paid $ 4 a day for attending a one-hour program outside regular class hours, school officials said. During the hour, which may be before or after classes, they will receive tutoring and help with homework, get counseling on their attitude toward school, and prepare for the state high school proficiency tests. The test is required in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> to receive a diploma. `` This is fairer because the student has to come in the hour before or the hour after school, which is a good commitment to make,'' <PERSON> Lock </PERSON> said. `` We think it will accomplish similar goals but not attract the type of attention the other -LRB- program -RRB- seemed to attract.'' Students will be required to complete the program requirements five days in a row to receive the all-or-nothing weekly payment. The revised program will be trimmed back considerably, with the budget slashed from $ 108,000 to $ 50,000, <PERSON> Nogueira </PERSON> said. The funding comes from a federal grant under the Job Training and Partnership Act. <PERSON> Nogueira </PERSON> said less money was budgeted because not all those eligible can be persuaded to participate. Last year, for example, only 48 of 130 targeted students took part. An analysis also found the program is not appropriate for students with especially high absentee rates or disciplinary problems, <PERSON> Lock </PERSON> said. Despite the controversy, officials said the program was a success. At the end of the school year, 70 percent of the 48 participants had passed the high school proficiency test. `` We're not suggesting this is the way for everyone to go but we do know financial incentives are part of our culture,'' <PERSON> Nogueira </PERSON> said.
