<HEAD>American Companies Scramble to Get Ready for 1992 in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American companies are scrambling to make sure they are not shut out of the lucrative new market that will be formed in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in 1992. That's when the 12 nations of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- EEC -RRB- remove the many trade barriers separating them. `` We're living through a historic period in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. It is all happening. You ignore it at your peril,'' said <PERSON> Eamonn </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> affairs manager for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. `` Every aspect of doing business in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is going to change.'' In response, top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies are opening special offices, reviewing business strategies and hiring consultants to get ready for the next decade when the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> becomes a single market of 320 million consumers. `` American companies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are taking the issue very, very seriously,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> di </PERSON> <PERSON> Pretoro </PERSON>, who recently assumed his post as senior vice president for <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> affairs for <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>. Many executives say the far-reaching changes, while spurring greater competition, should lead to reduced costs and bigger sales. `` You're going to operate in a much more difficult environment,'' said <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Patron </PERSON>, government affairs manager for <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. `` -LRB- But -RRB- if you play your cards right, you will benefit substantially.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials, though, worry that the Europeans might use their newfound togetherness to try to keep out <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and other foreign competition. <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Kingon </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview, `` What I'm afraid of ... is that when the barriers come down, the competition among themselves is going to be so great ... that there will be an instinctive protectionist push.'' European officials might decide, he said, `` all right we'll open it up internally, but we'll have to limit it externally.'' `` They insist it wo n't happen,'' he said. `` I hope they're right. Community officials dismiss concerns they will create a `` Fortress <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'' in 1992. `` These fears are totally unjustified,'' <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s top trade official, said in a recent speech. The idea of the European-wide market is to reduce the barriers that keep goods, services, people and money from moving freely among the 12 <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries: <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. They would, put simply, become more like the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> where people and goods, with some exceptions, can travel freely from state to state. The Europeans have drawn up a list of 285 steps that need to be taken to remove physical, technical and fiscal obstacles to unity. Their deadline for completing the task is the end of 1992. So far, 92 of the measures have been adopted. The 1992 pace has quickened dramatically since February when <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> leaders agreed on measures to solve a long-standing dispute over the trading bloc's budget. With their money woes apparently out of the way, officials have turned their attention to fashioning the single market. Many big <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies with strong European ties do not expect discriminatory moves against their operations but rather believe they stand to gain when the barriers are removed. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>, external affairs manager at <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s office in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, cites such statements by <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> chief executive <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> as one made in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION>: `` Companies working inside the community will continue to be welcomed. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> conducts a share of its R & amp; D -LRB- research and development -RRB- in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. For us, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> is a European company.'' `` We feel zero threat,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Telegdy </PERSON>, director of government affairs for <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. `` We feel we stand to gain and have nothing to lose by the European integration,'' Dow estimates the new <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> will mean savings of roughly $ 50 million annually from, among other things, lower transportation costs, product standardization and simplification of accounting procedures. But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials still voice concern about Americans being kept out. Deputy Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON> recently cautioned the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, `` The creation of a single market that reserves ` <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for Europeans' would be bad for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and for the multilateral economic system.'' `` We would find unacceptable,'' he said in a speech in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, `` measures that would limit market access for third countries and discriminate against foreign companies already established or that wish to establish in the community.'' <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crossick </ORGANIZATION>, senior <ORGANIZATION> partner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> L </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belmont </ORGANIZATION>, a Brussels-based consulting firm that counts top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies among its clients, said, `` To a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> player well-prepared and integrated in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the opportunities appear to exceed the threats.'' But, he added, `` the Fortress <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> question is of serious concern. We do n't want to hype it up _ that's a danger. But it could be a serious issue.'' A key concern, analysts say, is the growing use of `` reciprocity'' in <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> discussions about how much access foreign companies will have in sectors, such as financial services, not yet covered by international trade rules. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> said in recent speeches that the test of reciprocity would be used when a foreign financial institution asks permission to operate in an EEC country. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, he said, `` will check on a case-by-case basis whether similar institutions from all member states are given the same treatment in the non-community country concerned.'' `` If not,'' he continued, `` the authorization procedure will be suspended until we have ensured reciprocity by negotiating with the non-community country concerned.'' <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>, vice president of corporate external affairs for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, said the reciprocity issue could disrupt the financial markets now operating efficiently in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` If the community tries to do a lockout,'' he said, `` they risk cutting off their noses to spite their face.'' Foreign money, he added, could be driven out of the community to offshore banking centers. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials want the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> to apply a standard of national treatment to foreign firms so that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks and other operations will be treated in the new market just like <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> companies. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials also are concerned the community will extend to all 12 countries limits that a few have on imports of certain products and that it will bow to protectionist demands from special interests in fashioning commercial and industrial policies. `` This could result in new and greater discrimination in the areas, for example, of right of establishment, mergers and acquisitions, government procurement, subsidies, local content requirements and standards and certification,'' said <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON>.
