<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note Sept. 26 trial date in 33rd graf, ``The Rivaltas .. .,''
which is 11th graf of first add.</NOTE>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> NEW </LOCATION> <LOCATION> YORK </LOCATION> _ Stringent security on the one hand and a trusting openness on the other mark the dealing in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s exotic Diamond District. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> was an outsider who proved remarkably successful in that environment _ until that day when she was murdered and the $ 500,000 in diamonds she had been carrying disappeared. It's a story worthy of a movie plot.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s tradition-bound <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> was different _ a young Italian-American Catholic woman in an industry dominated by Jewish men, an outsider who went to school for the expertise more often passed down through families. But it is not <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON>'s success in the diamond business that its denizens will remember. <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON>, 33, disappeared Feb. 4 along with more than $ 500,000 in diamonds, the day after a proposed sale fell through. In June, her body was found in the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>; she had been bludgeoned to death. Only one of the six missing jewels has been recovered. `` She was just an innocent victim,'' says <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Hruska </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewelry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The lesson that has to be learned from this is that ... you have to take care of yourself, you have to take every precaution.'' Aside from <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON>'s death, there have been three other murders this year in the block of midtown bounded by 46th and 47th streets and Fifth and Sixth avenues, which is the Diamond District's heart. That's high for a business area, says a detective. A walk down 47th Street, where gold-filled windows front onto rooms crowded with jewelry-laden counters, suggests the business's inherent risk: Gems are easily portable, readily negotiable, highly valuable things Danger, says one dealer, is `` an occupational hazard.'' But some say something is wrong when a young, relatively inexperienced, unprotected woman is allowed to carry half a million dollars worth of jewels to an unknown prospective buyer. As is customary in the industry, <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> only had to sign memos to receive the diamonds on consignment from a broker with whom she'd done business before `` This was an enormous deal and way beyond <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>'s league,'' says <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON>'s friend from childhood. `` If things are n't changed it can happen again and it will happen again.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Born in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and raised on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> earned a two-year associate's degree in business and went to work in advertising for more than seven years. Slim, athletic, with long dark brown hair, she is remembered by friends and associates as sincere, kind, family-oriented. In 1986, she decided to go into the jewelry business. `` She was always interested in things like archaeology and gems and stones and physics,'' <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> started out selling what are called `` findings'' _ jewelry parts and raw metal. When her interest turned to diamonds she entered the <ORGANIZATION> Gemological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in June 1987, to learn what are known in the trade as the four C's _ color, clarity, carat weight and cut. She emerged an accredited expert in the quality of diamonds and other precious stones. She had met a broker, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON>, who says he became her `` mentor in the diamond business.'' He describes her as a woman of `` simple elegance,'' one who wore little makeup or jewelry. Her eye, he says, was on the top. If so, she was in the right place: Last year, 80 percent of the $ 3.4 billion in non-industrial diamonds that entered the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> came into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Much of the actual diamond dealing is conducted in secure offices or in bourses like the <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> on West 47th Street. There, amid high-tech security and state-of-the-art business conveniences backed by three computer systems, men in long beards lean across narrow tables littered with pieces of white waxed paper. Tweezers in hand and loupe to eye, they trade tiny crystals potentially worth millions of dollars. It is a business based in trust. Deals are sealed and stones change hands on just a handshake and the words `` mazel and brucha'' _ Yiddish for `` luck and blessing.'' A date of payment is agreed upon, a memo is signed. Should one side renege, the dispute goes to the club's arbitration. Though she started out in sales, and earned money doing free-lance deals during and after her student days, <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> apparently decided she did not belong in this part of the industry. When she disappeared, she had worked several times on a free-lance basis verifying gems at <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s, the auctioneers. She was also interviewing for a full-time job in diamond merchandising at <ORGANIZATION> Tiffany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The women who do make their living dealing in the <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> know well the rules of this exotic world, where some very Orthodox men will put a stone on the counter for them to pick up, rather than risk touching a woman to whom they are n't married. They are also well acquainted with its dangers. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Laufer </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, 35, runs the retail and wholesale jewelry exchange started by her father. Two years ago, her husband, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, 35, left the store to meet someone who owed him money. He was carrying about $ 6,000 worth of jewelry, his wife said. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>'s body was found in February 1987, in a <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> swamp. He had been shot four times, in the head and chest.
</TEXT>
