<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: and chest.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 For most of <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON>'s short time in the business, she was not confronted by the dangers. While in school, she began to do free-lance sales, first of finished jewelry, later of actual gems. As time went on, <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON> said, she began to ask for larger and more important stones for clients. She continued to free-lance after graduating in December, and on Feb. 1, <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON> says, <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> called and said she had a prospective buyer for investment-quality diamonds. At about 5:30 p.m. on Feb. 3, <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON> says, he put <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> in a taxi. She was to deliver an engagement ring to a customer at 6 p.m. and then meet a diplomat from a Third World nation who was supposedly interested in the diamonds. The meeting had been arranged through two Italian brothers who were friends of <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON>'s. <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON> says she did n't seem overly excited. He had given her stones worth as much as $ 250,000 before. When he'd heard nothing by midnight, <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON> said, he called <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON>'s apartment and she told him the meeting had been canceled at the last minute. <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> agreed to meet at noon the next day, when she would return the diamonds and hand over $ 3,500 from the sale of the engagement ring. She called an associate of the broker's around 11:30 a.m. and said she was on her way. She was last reported seen shortly after noon in the vestibule of her <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> building. No one has been charged in <LOCATION> Mangiameli </LOCATION>'s death or the theft of the diamonds. But authorities say the brothers, <PERSON> Fausto </PERSON> and <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivalta </PERSON>, were arrested on April 11 and charged with interstate transportation of stolen property _ one of the stones _ and are suspects in <LOCATION> Mangiameli </LOCATION>'s disappearance. When <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON>'s body was found June 9, the medical examiner's office said she had not been dead for very long, `` certainly ... not months. But that estimate later was rescinded because of the water temperature and other variables, according to office spokeswoman <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Borakove </PERSON>. Now, <PERSON> Borakove </PERSON> says, `` We're still not prepared to give any information out on the timing of the death.'' The Rivaltas have been held without bail since their arrest and face trial Sept. 26 in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> federal court. The federal complaint against the pair alleges that two weeks after <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> disappeared, <PERSON> Fausto </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivalta </PERSON> sold a pear-shaped diamond at a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> pawnshop for $ 14,000. An appraiser identified it as one of the six missing gems. Both brothers gave separate videotaped statements to the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> district attorney's office in March saying they did not buy diamonds shown to them on Feb. 2 by <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON>. <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> says that <PERSON> Fausto </PERSON> _ who lived in the same apartment building as <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> _ described himself as an interior designer. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> <PERSON> Childers </PERSON> says that at the time of his arrest, <PERSON> Fausto </PERSON>, 33, was on probation on a burglary charge in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and had been arrested several times in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, mostly for `` theft-related'' crimes. <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON> say they never met <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivalta </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> described to <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON> as a vice president of the brokerage <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc In an affidavit dated April 28, <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON>, 48, described himself as `` on leave of absence'' from the firm. But the company's personnel director, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacoff </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON> started as a security guard in April 1984 and worked his way up to the post of clerk in the international operations department. He said he was fired Feb. 26 for failing to return from vacation. Some people in the <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> say <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> was wrong to carry diamonds to meet someone she did n't know. Yet many dealers and brokers carry jewels around, and danger is widely regarded as inevitable in a business that deals daily in some of the world's most precious objects The district contains a heavy presence of uniformed and undercover police and private security guards, but it is n't always enough. Recent deaths include that of a man who was thrown to the ground and struck his head on the sidewalk during a mugging in June. At one end of the spectrum are Colombian criminals who squirt their prey with ketchup and commit robbery while the hapless victim is trying to clean it up. `` Sometimes they end up with $ 100,000 score and sometimes they end up with someone's lunch,'' says Detective <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Midtown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Precinct </LOCATION>. Then there are the Soviet emigres who work a more sophisticated con, finding it easier to set up a deal and get a foot inside the door of a jewelry business than `` the average black kid from <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>,'' he says. In such an environment, it can take just one mistake to become a casualty. <PERSON> Fischler </PERSON> says <PERSON> Mangiameli </PERSON> was `` smart, maybe a little naive and that's why she got conned. But nobody's perfect.'' In the <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, danger `` is an occupational hazard in the sense that there'll always be someone who'll try and put a scam on you,'' says <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>'s widow, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>. She too carries jewels _ and takes a different route home every night. But, she says, `` you ca n't go to work every day thinking that someone is out to kill you, because then you may as well just stay in bed.''
</TEXT>
