<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV25   09-12 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 25,0779</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pianist-arranger <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, one of the members of the original cast back for a revival of `` Ai n't Misbehavin','' thinks the Fats <PERSON> Waller </PERSON> musical is even better than when it opened 10 years ago And that original production was good enough to lead to successful Broadway revues of music by <PERSON> Eubie </PERSON> <PERSON> Blake </PERSON> -LRB- `` Eubie'' -RRB- and <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellington </PERSON> -LRB- `` Sophisticated Ladies'' -RRB-. Other members of the original Broadway cast _ <PERSON> Nell </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, <PERSON> Armelia </PERSON> <PERSON> McQueen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Charlaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodard </PERSON>, <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON> _ are at the Ambassador Theater, again singing songs that the late composer-pianist-singer <PERSON> Fats </PERSON> <PERSON> Waller </PERSON> made into hits. <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> sits in for <PERSON> Waller </PERSON> at the upright piano. `` There have been many extraordinarily good casts,'' <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> says. `` But none of them generate the kind of electricity that this group does. This show has taken on a deeper dimension. I do n't know if that's visible to everybody. The singers are doing the same thing they did before and as great as it was, it seems to be better now. I think I'm playing better now. `` What we were attempting, and I think we do, is to capture, be custodians of and illuminate the spirit of <PERSON> Fats </PERSON> <PERSON> Waller </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> says. `` We're not just giving lip service to songs like ` T'ain' t Nobody's Biz-ness If I Do' and his saying, ` One never know, do one It's for fun.'' One song, `` Black and Blue,'' is n't intended to be funny, but sometimes the audience laughs as the song begins. The laughter trails off as they realize it's serious. `` All of a sudden, <ORGANIZATION> Fats </ORGANIZATION>, who's telling everybody your feet's too big and this man is fat and greasy and being the buffoon _ for which he got a lot of flack in his lifetime _ decides to create a very strong protest song,'' <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> says. `` People have been having such a good time they ca n't believe right away he's not kidding.'' `` Ai n't Misbehavin''' has been touring, drawing audiences steadily over 10 years, with different casts. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Oxley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> McDaniels </PERSON>, who've done the show often, currently play piano on Tuesday nights and Wednesday matinees, when <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> is off. <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> confesses that he really does n't play like <PERSON> Fats </PERSON> <PERSON> Waller </PERSON>, `` except in certain things.'' `` I use some of his stride piano idioms,'' he says. `` Stride is ` oom pah,' a rhythmic background effect, like a band. Fats was exuberant and he showed it in his percussiveness. He was able to do stride with his left hand and play other stuff up in the right hand. `` In the late 1930s and early 1940s the art of stride piano playing, and boogie-woogie, were incredible. I can tell you they are very difficult to do.'' <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> was hired as arranger when `` Ai n't Misbehavin''' started as a musical revue at the off-Broadway <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. `` The orchestra is built around the piano,'' he says. `` Fats never had a band. He called it Fats <PERSON> Waller </PERSON> and his rhythm. He used a drummer, bassist and sometimes a guitarist.'' Later, <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> reluctantly agreed to play on-stage piano as well. <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Juilliard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> graduate, decided early in life to concentrate on arranging instead of composing or performing. He was intimidated by the great jazz pianists then working. `` I always tell people I was frightened by <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Tatum </PERSON> at an early age,'' he says. `` Then <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> came along.'' He composed the music for an off-Broadway musical comedy, `` Crystal Tree.'' `` I'm not a bad composer,'' he says, `` but that's something you ca n't do offhand You have to do it every day; it's not a part-time job. When he arranges, <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> says, he starts with pinning down what is to be communicated. `` When I get a job like ` Miss <ORGANIZATION> Teen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION>' for TV, I do n't need to go into that depth. I just generally do because that's how I got brought up. When I get these gigs, I work twice as hard as anybody else.'' <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> recently arranged two albums, of Dixieland and <PERSON> Gershwin </PERSON> music, for the Canadian Brass. `` There is nothing in those two hours of music that is improvised and they say Dixieland should be improvised. `` I think I was successful. It's the essence of what Dixieland might have been if they'd all had the technique these boys have got. I strive for that _ the essence _ a lot.''
</TEXT>
