<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Soviets Coming Back to China and Welcome Is Warm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-China-Soviet Border, b0798</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANZHOULI, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At the Crying Deer Restaurant on <LOCATION> Sino-Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION>, chef <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhaomin </PERSON> cracks a toothless grin and runs to the back to grab two plates of his famous salad. `` Soviet friends, you've returned,'' he shouts. `` Soviet friends, we welcome you.'' <PERSON> Andrev </PERSON> <PERSON> Vedernikov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> Evdokimov </PERSON>, railway workers in this town on the Soviet border, have come back for another meal. Down the street, at the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, members of the Soviet Friendship Delegation from <LOCATION> Zabaikalsk </LOCATION> dance the night away with their counterparts from the <ORGANIZATION> Manzhouli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sino-Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friendship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. At the close of the evening, under revolving green and red disco lights, <PERSON> Xue </PERSON> <PERSON> Guiyuan </PERSON>, a Chinese trade official, waxes melodramatic. `` Two great nations are becoming friends again,'' he says. `` Two peoples are moving closer together.'' On train No. 390, heading east from <LOCATION> Manzhouli </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shamrett </LOCATION>, 48, and her son, <PERSON> Kostya </PERSON>, 19, are off to see relatives in <LOCATION> Harbin </LOCATION>, the provincial capital of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heilongjiang </LOCATION> province. `` We come from <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>,'' announces Mrs. <PERSON> Shamrett </PERSON> in rusty Chinese, learned in the five years she spent in <LOCATION> Harbin </LOCATION> as a youngster. `` It's been more than 30 years since I saw my brother.'' `` I hope to learn about kung-fu,'' said her son. `` It's becoming very popular back home.'' Just as trade has blossomed between <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, so have contacts between Chinese and Soviets. Since last year, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has allowed Soviets to return to its border provinces to visit relatives who stayed after relations between the two countries deteriorated in the late 1950s. The Soviets have done the same for Chinese with family in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Both countries also have dropped visa requirements for businessmen. <PERSON> Vedernikov </PERSON>, 30, and <PERSON> Evdokimov </PERSON>, 29, who work on Soviet freight trains between <LOCATION> Manzhouli </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zabaikalsk </LOCATION>, studied Chinese for five years at the <ORGANIZATION> Chita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pedagological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, about 180 miles from the Chinese border. Now they handle freight and mail, which have both increased markedly as trade between the countries rises. `` I had a choice between a job as a teacher or work on this train,'' said <PERSON> Evdokimov </PERSON>, speaking a mixture of Chinese and English. `` The job is boring, but I wanted to see <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. It fascinates me strongly.'' <PERSON> Vedernikov </PERSON> hopes to parlay his excellent Chinese into a job as a businessmen. `` I was trained to be a translator, but when I finished school in 1980 things were still bad between our countries so there were no jobs. Now there's much possibility,'' he said. The two men said they were impressed at the economic growth in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, especially at the relative abundance of vegetables and consumer goods. They also noted the increasing number of private businesses, of which the Crying Deer is one. `` Private or cooperative businesses in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are just beginning, but here they've been going on for about five years now,'' said <PERSON> Vedernikov </PERSON>. `` I think they can teach us very much.'' Sun, a 61-year-old former member of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s famed <ORGANIZATION> Eighth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Route </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and regarded as the best chef in town, agrees. `` I say open the borders wide and we'll show them how to make money,'' he said. `` That would be a twist.''
