<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Sweet Hearts Dance''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Television sitcoms have always known about it. Presidential politicians have embraced it. Now the movies are redisovering the potent appeal of The Family. `` Sweet Hearts Dance'' is the latest variation on the family theme, and it is an unexpected winner. No movie has so touched the heart since `` Terms of Endearment.'' Of course, you might expect `` Sweet Hearts Dance'' to be impressive when you note that the writer is <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. His play and movie of `` On Golden Pond'' were exquisite depictions of the joys and sorrows of old age. Now he focuses on a younger generation of marrieds and about-to-be marrieds, contributing an equal portion of humanity and understanding. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarandon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> have been married long enough for boredom to have set in. She tolerates his macho pastimes, he largely ignores her womanly longings. He is a builder, and their life in a <LOCATION> Norman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rockwellian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> town is comfortable, familiar and dull. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s best buddy is <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>. He is a school principal, a bit dull but by no means dumb. A devout bachelor, he is attracted to the new teacher in town, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>, but is wary of commitment. The story is told in seasons, each framed like an old-time calendar. The seasons change, as do the relationships of the four characters. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, rankling under his loss of freedom, finally moves out of the family house. After a <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> vacation with his lodge members, the four lives are sorted out, more or less. A synopsis makes it seem that not much happens in `` Sweet Hearts Dance.'' But it is constantly engrossing, tender without excess sentiment, and often hilarious. Amazingly, the film is the first feature directed by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenwald </PERSON>, a television veteran who has a bright future in films. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s script and <PERSON> Greenwald </PERSON>'s direction give the four stars equal opportunity to shine. With her wise, wondering eyes, <PERSON> Sarandon </PERSON> is the ideal portrayer of the 1980s woman. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> is a revelation, displaying none of his `` Miami Vice'' schtick. <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> is ideal for the role as the intelligent innocent, and <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> -LRB- `` Big'' -RRB- registers again as a bright screen presence. `` Sweet Hearts Dance'' has so many moments to cherish that it should probably be seen twice for full appreciation. The Tri-Star release was produced by <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Lourie </PERSON>. The rating is R, mostly for language. Running time: 101 minutes.
