<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Faded, Scarred Rothko Murals on Display</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The late abstract expressionist <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> said he was less interested in color and form than in expressing human emotions. Now, as <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> displays a colossal series of Rothko murals, the consequences of the artist's philosophy _ as well as years of neglect _ have become clear. The three murals, some 500 square feet of oil and acrylic on canvas, have badly faded in the sunlight during the 16 years they hung in a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> dining room, so much so that they actually have changed color. They also suffered rips, scratches and splatters caused by bumping chairs and spilled food. On one panel is scrawled the name <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> The </PERSON> institution for years was criticized for what was believed to be its mishandling of the paintings, particularly from devotees of the so-called <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> of modern artists, co-founded by <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> before World War II. A new study conducted by <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> scholars has turned up two prime culprits: the artist and <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> contributed to the demise of the works by using a highly unstable paint _ lithol red _ to form the background of all three murals. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> made matters worse by failing to protect the canvases from sunlight and careless visitors. `` <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> has gotten so much bad press about the <PERSON> Rothkos </PERSON> that we did n't feel it would matter if we said again, ` they're in tough shape,''' said <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON>, head conservator at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>. The color used by <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> has a reputation as a `` fugitive pigment'' and its fleeting existence on <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON>'s canvas explains why. The artist apparently had no idea in 1962 when he completed the paintings that the color was susceptible to fading. His attitude toward the subject was revealed in a conversation related by <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, head conservator of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in the late 1960s: `` I said, ` What kind of paint do you use?''' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> recalled in a telephone interview. `` He said, ` I use oil paint and if I run out I go downstairs to the Woolworths and buy whatever's there.' He should have known better.'' The five-and-dime paint was n't up to the conditions in the sun-filled penthouse suite in Harvard Square that housed the murals from 1963 until 1979 when, scratched, scuffed and faded, they were removed to a vault. A wine-dark crimson, chosen in honor of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, formed the background color of the murals. On two panels, the color faded to a dull, denim blue _ nearly <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> blue. And to make matters worse, the color faded unevenly, ruining the intended uniformity of background that made the room vibrate with color. `` It was like walking into a medieval cathedral at sunset,'' said <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who helped unroll and mount the paintings when they arrived at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>. The paintings are on display at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Sackler </PERSON> museum through Oct. 2. They are arranged in the same configuration as their original setting in the university's <ORGANIZATION> Holyoke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> but are now far from any direct sunlight. `` If -LRB- <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> -RRB- could see the extent to which these particular color relations had been so drastically altered he would most likely disown the paintings,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> associate art Professor <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Chave </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> expert. `` I think they're relics, basically. They're artifacts.'' The paintings still have value, in <LOCATION> Chave </LOCATION>'s view, much the way <PERSON> Leonardo </PERSON>'s `` The Last Supper'' can move a viewer despite extensive deterioration. `` They were allowed to be exposed to an incredible amount of light in their original installation and that's why they faded so drastically,'' <PERSON> Chave </PERSON> said. `` No one was doing anything about it. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> really did not pay attention to what was happening.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Coolidge </PERSON>, former director of the Fogg and one of those directly involved in promoting <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON>'s donation of the murals to <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, places most of the blame on the artist. `` <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> was passionate to create a room, but he had not the slightest idea what was involved,'' <PERSON> Coolidge </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> officials, he said, were loathe to `` question the quality of his technique. ... We were certainly unprepared for the speed with which they went.'' <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> was contacted once about the fading of the murals, <PERSON> Chave </PERSON> said. He rejected a proposal to varnish the canvases to protect them. In 1970, at age 67, <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> committed suicide, 57 years after he came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. After his death, confusion and controversy over control of <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON>'s estate complicated any decision about the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> paintings. Since then, another, even larger set of murals at the <LOCATION> Rothko </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> has had to undergo treatment because a chemical used in their varnish reacted with the atmosphere to create white splotches on black paint. But <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranmer </PERSON>, former conservator of the <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> foundation, said <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> is only one of many modern artists whose works have fallen victim to decay. `` Because of the emphasis on this it does look like <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON>'s the only bad boy in town,'' <PERSON> Cranmer </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Willem </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Kooning </PERSON> used mayonnaise on his paintings. Longevity is low on the totem pole.''
</TEXT>
