<HEAD>Music Makers: Brenda Believes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISSA M. VECCHIONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Like the title of her current hit single, <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> says she still believes stardom will be hers. `` I believe in myself, but I know it takes time,'' says the 21-year-old singer, whose first hit single, `` I Still Believe'' has climbed the charts to the Top 40. She recently talked about her career in an interview at the offices of <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>. She compared herself to a long list of contemporary artists, including <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, before actually calling herself a `` young <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Summer </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> has been heavily influenced by rhythm and blues and Latin sounds, and she likes her music to have those elements. However, she does n't like to be compared to other young artists such as <PERSON> Tiffany </PERSON> or <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>. She says they're too `` pure.'' She prefers being thought of as sexier. `` I'm a romantic,'' <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> said. Her self-titled LP contains the popular love ballad, `` I Still Believe,'' as well as more upbeat tracks, including the hit `` What You See Is What You Get.'' Most of these danceable tunes portray love and happiness, with one pop tune that warns against drunken driving. Born <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON> on <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, she took the last name <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> because `` that's what I've always wanted to be, a star.'' She started singing in choirs in grammar and junior high school. `` They always had choirs that you could join as a hobby, so I took singing because I felt it was fun,'' she said. <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> dropped out of high school to put out her first album, `` I Want Your Love,'' on Mirage Records. She later realized a lot more than singing was involved in the music business and that there was a lot more to life than singing, so she went back to school to get her diploma. Her first big break came when she appeared in the movie `` Beat Street,'' a 1984 dance film, as an auditioning singer. She also co-wrote the songs `` Shadows of the Night'' and `` Vicious Beat'' for the movie's soundtrack. Her other appearances were with an all-girl breakdancing group called The Dynamic Dolls. They once performed in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for President and Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Though her father, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, who sang with the pop group Spiral Staircase, was in the music business, he was n't her main influence. `` My father did n't influence me, my mother influenced me,'' <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> said. `` She always told me I would be successful and if I wanted to do something I could do it. My father? I was happy that he was my dad and he had a record out, but I wanted to show him that I could do just as he could so he would be proud of me. Now I'm doing it for me.'' <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> spends a lot of time on the road touring. After meetings with managers, voice lessons and family visits to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, she enjoys returning to the tranquility of her new home in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bergen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, where she's writing songs for an upcoming album. What's does <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> see in her future? `` I want to be married by 24 and have a baby by 25,'' said the singer, who already has names picked out for the five children she wants. `` They'll be my audience in case there's not enough of one. I want to be like my mom, who had seven. It's like camp.'' Another movie apperance is n't on her agenda, though. `` I've been asked to do movies but have n't taken anyone up on their offer because I'm so into my music right now,'' she said. `` I'm trying to concentrate on my shows and do a good performance so people can enjoy me and say, ` I'm going to go out and buy that album.''' Asked about doing television, <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> perked up and said with a big smile, `` I want to do the Cosby Show. I want to meet <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON>.''
