<HEAD>U.S. Troops To Get New Insect Repellent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEB RIECHMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FREDERICK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s going to war against the insect repellent that troops have been using for two decades. `` The old one melted plastic watch crystals and eyeglass frames and left an oily feeling on their skin,'' said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, who helped coordinate the new version. `` Generally, they just did n't like it.'' It also smelled so bad that `` there was a feeling, particularly in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, that an enemy could smell you if you were wearing it,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The new repellent, which looks like hand cream and comes in a green plastic tube, will be in the hands of servicemen by next summer. It was developed in a $ 4.3 million effort directed by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Material </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Activity </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Detrick </LOCATION>, and was prompted in part by a 1983 survey. Forty-five percent of the 1,542 soldiers questioned seldom or ever used the repellent issued since the 1960s, and 62 percent said the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> needed a better one. Fifty-four percent used commercial repellents because they smelled better, felt better on their skin and lasted longer. The old version was 75 percent diethyltoluamide, commonly called deet, and 25 percent alcohol, <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said. The new product, 35 percent deet and with no alcohol, has a milder odor. It protects for up to 12 hours, vs. four hours with the old version and does n't wash or wear off as easily The new repellent has been tested in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. It protects against disease-carrying arthropods, such as mosquitos, chiggers, fleas, biting flies, deer flies and stable flies. The insects can carry diseases such as malaria, scrub typhus, lyme disease, dengue fever, sand fly fever and Rift Valley Fever. It still will melt and cloud some `` cheap plastic items, if you let it set for a while,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said. `` But it's not as bad as the old product that would make a hole in the plastic.''
</TEXT>
