<FIRST>r f PM-OilRecords     09-12 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Records,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Lists Oil Industry Records And Trivia</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First for AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From the first dry hole to `` Big <PERSON> Bertha </PERSON>,'' the world's most productive drill bit, the records, trivia and history that give the `` oil bidness'' its unique, colorful character have been chronicled by an industry trade journal. `` Drilling Magazine,'' updating a list it first ran five years ago, is giving its 20,000 readers _ primarily well-site operators _ some targets to shoot for and records to brag about. `` It's sort of the oil industry's Guinness Book,'' says Editor <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Killalea </PERSON>, who compiled the facts appearing in the current issue of the bi-monthly magazine. `` I'm very much interested in the curiosity and the oddball. While penetration rates and footage distances are incredible, they do n't grip the imagination.'' So besides records like the deepest, first and most productive well, the magazine's list includes such items as how the term `` derrick'' got its name, where the first dry hole was drilled and the strangest well blowout. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil industry is generally given a birth year of 1859 with the discovery of crude in <LOCATION> Venango </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, on land owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Watson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Brewer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The well generally is known as the Drake Discovery Well, so named for <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Drake </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Seneca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haven </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, the well owner. But what's less well-known is the first dry hole, in neighboring <LOCATION> Warren </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. It also carries the distinction of the world's second oil well, started four days after the Drake Well More dubious, it's the first well in which oil tools got stuck. Magazine editors also have decided the strangest well blowout occurred in April 1, 1984, in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pinto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, when the Mitchell Lease No. 1 well blew and was shut quickly as a safety precaution. The next day, however, an explosion two miles away was blamed on the shut well. Apparently pressure built up and traveled along a layer of rock and salt 250 feet underground until surfacing two miles away. The term `` derrick,'' by the way, is named after a famous English hangman who skillfully practiced his trade around 1600. He was so notorious that his name was applied to anything that was hoisted or lifted. And in oil, a derrick is the structure that lifts pipe in and out of the hole. New entries to the record book include: _ The deepest water-depth oil discovery in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>: a 13,600-foot hole in 3,560 feet of water 55 miles east of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> delta _ The deepest water-depth drilling in the world: 7,520 feet, <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, Nov. 5, 1987 The hole reached 17,430 feet before the drillship was moved Feb. 16, 1988. _ The most productive drill bit: `` Big <PERSON> Bertha </PERSON>,'' a 17 -LCB- - inch bit manufactured by Houston-based Hycalog, drilled 18,016 feet in 16 runs in five <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> wells with no repair between The bit, used in 1987 and this year, made more holes in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> than any other single bit. And its mark of going through more than 30,000 cubic feet of rock could make it the most productive single drill bit of all time. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> state deep-drilling marks on the books include a well of 20,335 feet in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, set in 1979; 22,712 in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, reached in 1987; <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s 25,703 feet in 1980; 29,670 feet in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in 1982; and 31,441 feet in 1974 in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, which used to be the world's deepest and may be again. A 40,000-foot well being drilled in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, cited five years ago as the world's deepest, since then has caved in, according to unidentified sources quoted by Drilling Magazine. `` Glasnost or no glasnost, it's not the easiest thing to find out,'' <PERSON> Killalea </PERSON> says. `` I ultimately did discover that the well caved in a year and a half ago. So they do n't have that claim -LRB- of the world's deepest -RRB- any more.'' <PERSON> Killalea </PERSON> says he called the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Embassy </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for confirmation and was told to send a letter. `` They were very nice and told me they would get back to me,'' he says. `` I'm waiting to hear from them.''
</TEXT>
