<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Declines In August</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus fell 3.9 percent in August over a year ago and 31 percent from the previous month, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday. The surplus in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s international trade fell to $ 4.94 billion from $ 5.15 billion in August 1987 and $ 7.16 billion in July. In July the surplus had ended a streak of 15 consecutive months of declines to grow by 3.1 percent over the previous year's level. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> declined by 12.7 percent in August over the previous year to $ 3.25 billion, the ministry said. `` Looking at the overall trend, the volume and value of imports are growing and cutting into -LRB- <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s -RRB- surplus. The government is also stimulating domestic demand'' in an attempt to curtail its overseas trade surplus, said a <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Imports surged by 27.3 percent on a dollar basis from the previous year's level to a record $ 15.86 billion for August, the ministry said. Exports rose 18.2 percent in August from the previous year's figure to $ 20.80 billion, but declined 10.2 percent from $ 23.15 billion in July In measuring exports, officials pegged the dollar at 133.13 yen, compared with 150.83 yen one year earlier and 131.31 yen in July, while imports were determined at an exchange rate of 133.12 yen to the dollar, in contrast with 150.83 yen in August 1987 and 131.40 yen last month. The ministry said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> declined in part because of major hikes in imports of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> food in August. Imports of fish soared by 105.3 percent, while those of meat rose by 99.6 percent, the ministry reported. Imports of nonferrous metals also increased, growing by 140.4 percent over the previous year, it said. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> measures its trade on a customs-clearance basis, which includes freight and insurance costs in imports but not in exports. If those costs were included in both categories, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus would be higher.
</TEXT>
