<HEAD>EEC Concerned By U.S. Senate Approval Of Textile Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it hopes President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoes the textile and apparel trade bill sanctioned by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last week. European External Relations Commissioner <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> said that the bill, if signed into law, would `` inevitably lead to the collapse'' of the Multifiber Agreement, which regulates world trade in textiles. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> also claimed it would `` seriously jeopardize'' the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> round of international trade negotiations in which trade representatives are attempting to improve the global trade system, including easing trade barriers between countries. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved draft legislation Friday that would put limits on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports of textiles, apparel and shoes. The vote was too short, however, to override an expected veto by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The measure must also be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> before being sent to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> said that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s move `` can only add to existing uncertainty in world trade'' because it came soon after last month's enactment of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade bill which the European commission considers to be protectionist. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> said that he hoped the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration's opposition to the bill would be maintained and that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would veto the draft law White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> already said President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would veto the bill if it reaches his desk. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoed an earlier version of the textile trade bill last year after it was passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>.
