<HEAD>Book Publisher Agrees to Buyout By New York Investment Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Publishing giant <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, target of unwanted takeover offers for four months, said today that it will be bought by the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in a cash deal that values the company at $ 2.36 billion. The announcement came after reports surfaced that <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> officials had negotiated this weekend with <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION>, a private partnership that has helped other large companies thwart unwelcome takeovers. <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> specializes in leveraged buyouts, in which a company is acquired through mostly borrowed money repaid from the target company's profits or asset sales. <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> said in a brief announcement that <PERSON> Kolhberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> had formed a subsidiary to begin a tender offer of $ 85 cash per share for up to 26.1 million shares of the company, or 94 percent of the total. The offer values the company's 27.76 million shares at about $ 2.36 billion. The announcement was the latest twist in a takeover battle waged since May for <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>, a large New York-based publishing concern and leading supplier of college textbooks. The company owns other operations that range from the <ORGANIZATION> Berlitz </ORGANIZATION> foreign language training program to <PERSON> Katharine </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> clerical schools. A group headed by British publisher <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> had been attempting to buy <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> and last week offered to raise its $ 80-a-share offer to $ 84 a share. A group headed by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> has offered $ 75 a share. The company had spurned offers from both and sought to restructure itself to thwart a takeover by selling the information division. The Bass group, which owns about 9.2 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION>'s shares, had successfully challenged the move in court, but the company said today that because of the planned acquisition by <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> it is scrapping the restructuring plan Rumors that <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> had enlisted the help of <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> helped boost the price of the company's stock Friday by $ 3.62 -LCB- to $ 83.87 -LCB- in composite <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. In early trading today <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> rose to $ 84.62 -LCB-.
