<HEAD>UAW Workers at Caterpillar Vote to Authorize Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union voted overwhelmingly to authorize a strike against <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> if necessary, but a <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> official said today the move is routine during contract negotiations. The members of <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Local 974, which represents some 10,000 <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> workers in the <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> area, voted Sunday in favor of allowing their negotiators to call a strike if it is deemed necessary, said <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>, assistant director of the local's community action program `` It passed our local by a tremendous amount, by like 95 percent,'' <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> members who work for <ORGANIZATION> Deere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> also voted overwhelmingly over the weekend to authorize their negotiators to call a strike if necessary, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Casstevens </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s secretary-treasurer in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 13,500 active <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> workers and 3,500 laid-off workers, voted 95 percent in favor of the strike authorization, he said. <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> officials and union negotiators began contract talks on Aug. 3 and were scheduled to resume talks this week. Valentine, of the <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> local, said strike-authorization votes are `` something that's customarily done'' during contract talks. `` It gives the bargainers an edge knowing their people are backing them,'' Valentine said. `` It does give our bargainers the feeling that people are behind them and gives them the authorization to call a strike if things do n't work out and the talks break down.'' <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON> said Local 974 represents about half of <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> workers nationwide He said other locals also took strike-authorization votes, but that he was n't certain of the results. Contract talks were continuing, <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON> said.
