<SECOND>AM-Japan-Winnebagos, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitsubishi Corp. To Market U.S. Winnebago RVs in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Winnebagos, those behemoths of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s wide-open spaces, were launched in the home of the compact car on Monday with the blessings of the Japanese government. With a logo suggesting <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s forested mountains and blue lakes, the venture announced between <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Winnebago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, had the glitz of professional marketing. <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> coined the slogan Mobilie _ mobile plus `` ie,'' the word for home in Japanese _ to try to sell the 122 million Japanese on the American concept of family-style recreational vehicles as a way to enjoy their country's scenery. The Japanese government is seeking to cut <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s $ 60 billion annual trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by encouraging more imports of American goods into <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Lauding the linkup were <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Commerce Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hajime </PERSON> <PERSON> Tamura </PERSON>, the powerful Japanese minister of international trade and industry. <PERSON> Tamura </PERSON>, one of the top political figures in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, came to the lavish party <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> threw at a former imperial mansion, and he drew a public pledge from company President <PERSON> Shinroku </PERSON> <PERSON> Morohashi </PERSON> to go all-out to sell Winnebagos. `` If a Japanese trading house like <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> starts a full-fledged program, it will succeed without fail,'' <PERSON> Tamura </PERSON> said, asking <PERSON> Morohashi </PERSON> to shake hands with <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> and `` pledge to make an all-out effort to succeed.'' With a smile, <PERSON> Morohashi </PERSON> obliged. <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> commented: `` With <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> marketing this product, I predict that this will be an immediate success.'' The commerce secretary is here leading executives of 25 U.S. consumer-products companies on a mission to penetrate the big but difficult Japanese market. Their slogan is `` Market <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ with <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s best,'' and the products include jewelry, pet foods, furniture, sailboats, power boats and sporting goods. The party for <PERSON> Winnebago </PERSON> was the centerpiece of the weeklong mission, and the guests included members of the Diet, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s parliament, as well as <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> government officials <PERSON> Morohashi </PERSON> said his company regarded the motor home as `` one of the great achievements'' of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> industry and predicted it will be a success as more leisure time encourages the Japanese to do more things outdoors. `` The market is very promising for the future,'' he said. Only in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> could such a symbol of American gigantism be launched in a room where the decor included bonsai _ the purposely stunted trees that are a symbol of the miniaturism of this country of small cars and narrow roads. Gasoline costs almost $ 3.50 a gallon in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and previous attempts to market Japanese-made camper vans have fizzled because of the expense of fuel and lack of campgrounds for them. But <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is richer now, and <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> says legislation will encourage the spread of campgrounds. Winnebago Vice President <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Boman </PERSON>, who had four of his smaller RV models on display outside the mansion, said the 30-year-old company now exports only 0.5 percent of the 12,000 to 14,000 units produced annually. <PERSON> Boman </PERSON> hoped the <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> marketing will help increase exports to about 10 percent of production, all of which takes place in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has learned much from the Japanese, especially in motor manufacturing,'' he said. `` Now we hope to share with the Japanese people what we learned in our own experience in the leisure industry.'' The governor, who grew up in <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Winnebago </PERSON> is headquartered, expressed delight at the opening to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s market `` This is a very major step forward by American industry and we are very proud that a company based in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> is leading the way here in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said. As the party ended <PERSON> Boman </PERSON> was asked how he felt to have such lavish promotion and government backing. `` It's a great relationship,'' he said, `` and this has been a fantastic trip.''
