<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv13   09-12 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 13 ,0600</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday, Sept. 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>America's Open? Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The next time you hear your congressman defend trade protection through quotas, higher tariffs or `` buy <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' programs, you might consider asking him the cost. It is through this sort of question that patriotic fervor, which some people think does n't cost a cent, confronts the individual budgets of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> households. Good or bad, trade protection is costly, forcing up the prices of domestic and imported goods by amounts that might surprise most people. By one estimate, it costs every man, woman and child in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> an average of $ 270 a year. That estimate, by economist <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hufbauer </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, is based on his calculation of a total cost per year of $ 65 billion, or nearly double the tab as recently as 1980. How could that be, ask Americans who believe that the American economy is as remarkably open to foreigners as foreign markets are closed to Americans? <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>, who studied the matter for the <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, concluded that it is n't so, that `` contrary to popular belief, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has become more protectionist over the last decade.'' He says that 35 percent of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufactured goods were protected by some form of trade barrier in 1986, compared with just 8 percent in 1975. The result, he says, is that Americans are paying through the nose. In addition to raiding consuumers' pockets, he says trade barriers invite other countries to retaliate against American industries. He cites two incidents as examples: _ When the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposed tariffs on Canadian cedar in 1986, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> responded with restrictions on American computers and grains _ When the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> placed restrictions on $ 50 million worth of Chinese textiles in 1983, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> canceled <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> wheat contracts worth $ 699 million The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> maintains tariffs in excess of 20 percent on light trucks, ceramic tile, cedar shingles, fruit juice, footwear and clothing, among other goods. In some instances, quotas are added to tariffs. There are service restrictions as well. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> notes that the domestic air travel market is reserved for domestic airlines, and that only U.S.-registered ships are allowed to carry passengers and cargo between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ports In fact, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 ranked the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as no better than average in its amount of protected trade. The cost of trade protection is often obscured by other issues, mainly the preservation of jobs. But <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> cites a study made last year that shows more jobs were lost than created by protection of the textile industry. That study shows protectionist measures did indeed save about 46,000 textile jobs _ at an alleged cost of $ 220,000 each _ but that 52,440 jobs were destroyed in retailing, transportation and other import-dependent areas. Such examples, <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> indicates, are among the more publicized. But, he observes, hidden away in various regulatory areas are many lesser known limitations that inexorably add to the cost of living in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In insurance, for example, a common barrier forces foreign firms to pay higher state fees for licenses. Some state regulations require these companies to invest premiums within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. What it amounts to, says <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>, is that before politicians try to raise trade barriers they should consider the costs of those already on the books, including the net cost of jobs lost.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday, Sept. 13.</NOTE>
