<HEAD>London Shares End Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices finished slightly higher Monday in sluggish trading on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with the market lacking a motivating force to spur it into action. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 6.2 points, or 0.4 percent, at 1,744.6 at the close of trading. The index rose as much as 9.3 points in early trading, but then fell back to show a gain of just 3.8 points just before the 11:30 a.m. -LRB- local time -RRB- release of British reports on producer prices and retail sales in August. The figures were in line with market expectations and did n't alter share prices. Volume was light, with just 213.2 million shares changing hands, down from 380.6 million on Friday. Some market watchers said traders were awaiting several key economic reports from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> later this week. Others said the market remained stalled due to a lack of interest in committing funds to the market. `` It's a stalemate,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Larkum </PERSON>, stocks analyst at <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, adding that `` there's an intellectual feeling that the market is cheap but a gut feeling that prices are going down.''
