<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Plunges, Dollar Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Undermined by weakening oil prices, gold fell sharply Monday in volatile European trading. Gold finished $ 7.55 an ounce lower in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> after plunging $ 11.50 an ounce in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, where trading ended early because of a holiday. The dollar was mixed at the end of extremely quiet trading as market players sat on their positions before the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for July from the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Zurich traders said the plunge in gold prices, which began in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Friday, caught them completely by surprise. `` I hate to admit it, but we're tending weaker, psychologically, if not fundamentally,'' said one <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> trader. Weaker prices for oil and other commodities have calmed fears of inflation. That has dampened demand for gold, which investors historically have used as a hedge against inflation. But traders said trading activity was limited, although they reported good demand at lower prices around $ 417. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, financial activity was expected to be muted through Tuesday because of <PERSON> Rosh </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashana </PERSON>, the Jewish new year holiday, and traders said they anticipated the lull would keep the market a bit thinner than usual. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 419.25 a troy ounce, compared with $ 426.80 bid late Friday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was quoted at $ 418 when the market closed early, down from $ 429.50 late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 5.60 to close at $ 419.18. Silver bullion also fell sharply on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 6.41 a troy ounce, compared with $ 6.63 Friday. Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar inched up earlier in the day for no particular reason, but was knocked back by intervention by the West German central bank when it rose above 1.8500 marks. Dealers said they expect the dollar to stay in its current range until the July trade report Wednesday. `` We have a serious case of the trade figure scenario,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Deacon </PERSON>, senior dealer at EBC-Amro bank in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. In recent months, foreign exchange trading has stalled in the days before a trade balance report. Market expectations are for a monthly trade gap of between $ 11 billion and $ 12 billion, compared with $ 12.54 billion in June. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost $ 1.6958 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.6980 late Friday Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with late Friday: 1.8453 West German marks, down from 1.8490; 1.5535 Swiss francs, down from 1.5620; 6.2775 French francs, down from 6.2865; 2.0817 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0835; 1,378.50 Italian lire, down from 1,379.50; 1.2395 Canadian dollars, unchanged. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar edged up 0.47 yen to close at 133.42 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 133.50 yen.
</TEXT>
