<HEAD>Armtek Board Agrees To $561 Million Buyout By Mark IV</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one new graf after 8th graf pvs ``Mark IV filed suit
..'' to ADD that legal action will be dropped. Picks up 9th graf
pvs ``Formerly the ..''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Armtek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday accepted a sweetened $ 561.2 million buyout offer from its once-hostile suitor <ORGANIZATION> Mark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> IV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, ending a brief battle for the auto parts maker. Under the agreement, which was approved unanimously by <PERSON> Armtek </PERSON>'s board of directors, the <ORGANIZATION> Mark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> IV </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> MIV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acquisition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will pay $ 46 a share for all 12.2 million common shares outstanding, $ 2 a share higher than its previous offer `` It's a great price,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeScenza </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Before this takeover fight began, the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Armtek </ORGANIZATION> stock -RRB- price was in the low $ 30s. `` It's being taken over at a price 50 percent above what the market valued the stock at.'' The bidding for <PERSON> Armtek </PERSON> began earlier this summer with a $ 40-a-share offer from Mark IV. It was raised to $ 44 a share on Aug. 17. Neither Armtek Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Keefe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> nor any of the company's board members would comment on the merger, according to <ORGANIZATION> Armtek </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. Merger talks had been anything but friendly. After Mark IV made its first offer, the board directed company officials to explore all options, including recapitalization and possible third-party buyers. Mark IV filed suit against <PERSON> Armtek </PERSON> at the end of last month charging Armtek misued a variety of anti-takeover measures. Armtek had accused <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> IV </PERSON> of violating disclosure requirements of federal securities laws. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said all legal action will be dropped as a result of the merger agreement. Formerly the <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, New Haven-based Armtek makes plastics and specialty chemicals used in the automotive and other industries and employs 8,000 people worldwide. It sold the <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Pirelli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> for $ 197 million earlier this year. Mark IV, based in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, manufactures aerospace and defense, professional audio and information productions, and technical products.
