<SECOND>AM-World Bank-IFC,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developing Countries Reported Turning to Private Sector</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most of the Third World is turning from state industries to private enterprise as a source of growth, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, private sector affiliate of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday. The Washington-based lending institution in its 1988 report described this as `` a historic change'' in the global investment climate, and said it offers `` good prospects for accelerated and sustainable growth'' in developing countries. `` In most developing countries ... governments have come to rely ever more on private enterprise as an ` engine of growth','' said the <ORGANIZATION> IFC </ORGANIZATION> report. The corporation, owned by 133 <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> member countries, reported a record of 95 new investments totaling $ 1.3 billion for the year ended last June 30, an increase of 38 percent over the previous year. The investments helped fuel projects worth more than $ 5 billion in 449 companies in 78 developing countries, the report said. Investment approvals increased in every area of the world, with the largest increase over the previous year, 73 percent, registered in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> south of the <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> desert, the report said.
</TEXT>
