<HEAD>Dollar Eases in New York, Gold Hardly Changed After Plunging in
Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar weakened marginally Monday in light trading, reflecting what money brokers called their reluctance to speculate in advance of the government's market-jolting monthly trade deficit reports. Gold ended barely changed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after a wild day in which precious metals prices tracked the volatile oil market. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> quoted gold at $ 421.35 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EDT, down 10 cents from Friday. Currency traders said the dollar's behavior typified a pattern that has emerged in days just prior to the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s merchandise trade deficit reports, which have the potential of setting off sharp selloffs or rallies in the financial markets The July deficit figures are due Wednesday. `` The dollar stayed in a narrow range today and essentially went nowhere,'' said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Yannalfo </PERSON>, senior foreign exchange trader at <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> commodities futures concern. `` Everybody's waiting for that trade number. The consensus among foreign-exchange houses is for a July deficit of between $ 11 billion and $ 12 billion, compared with $ 12.54 billion in June. But the unpredictability of these numbers has made many traders reluctant to take risky positions in dollars until after the report is issued. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar edged up 0.47 yen to close at 133.42 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 133.50 yen. By the time trading concluded in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar weakened to 133.35 yen, off from 133.61 yen Friday. The dollar gained against the British pound in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where sterling was quoted at $ 1.6958 vs. $ 1.6980 Friday. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound strengthened a bit to $ 1.6974, more expensive than the $ 1.6970 price Friday. Other late-dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> vs. levels late Friday included: 1.8465 West German marks, down from 1.8493; 1.5540 Swiss francs, down from 1.5617; 1.2367 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2396; 6.2815 French francs, down from 6.2890; and 1,378.85 Italian lire, down from 1,382.125. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with late Friday: 1.8453 West German marks, down from 1.8490; 1.5535 Swiss francs, down from 1.5620; 6.2775 French francs, down from 6.2865; 2.0817 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0835; 1,378.50 Italian lire, down from 1,379.50; and 1.2395 Canadian dolars, unchanged. Traders were more active in the gold market, which has weakened recently because of speculation about a renewed oil-price war. Prices plunged in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> but rebounded in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, tracking the path of energy futures. Cheaper energy prices could partly erase the effects of inflation, historically a key reason that investors buy gold. `` For the last couple of weeks, the price of gold and precious metals have been following the oil market,'' said <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagelhout </PERSON>, a marketing analyst at <ORGANIZATION> A-Mark </ORGANIZATION> precious metals, a large trading concern in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` Oil went down under $ 13 a barrel and rallied back up over $ 14. Gold did the same thing. The market has not stabilized.'' On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold for current delivery closed at $ 421.20, unchanged from Friday, when prices closed sharply lower. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, gold plunged to $ 419.25, down from $ 426.80 late Friday; in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold fell to $ 418, down from $ 429.50 Friday; and in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> gold fell to $ 419.18 from $ 424.78 Friday. Silver followed a similar pattern, ending largely unchanged in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after plunging abroad. Silver eased .3 cent to $ 6.437 a troy ounce on the Comex. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, silver fell to $ 6.41, down from $ 6.63 Friday.
