<HEAD>Ford-Nissan To Make '92 Minivan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which holds just less than a fourth of the fast-growing minivan market with its <ORGANIZATION> Aerostar </ORGANIZATION>, announced plans Monday to join with <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to make a minivan in northeastern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The project, which is to deliver the new vehicles to showroom floors in three years, will involve a $ 1 billion <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> investment, about 90 percent of which is to be spent at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s van plant in <LOCATION> Avon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, company vice chairman <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said at a news conference. The factory, which paints and assembles bodies for <ORGANIZATION> Econoline </ORGANIZATION> and Club Wagon vans, will double in size to 2.2 million square feet and will employ another 1,300 people, bringing total employment to nearly 2,800. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Meisenhelder </PERSON> said the company first would draw employees from a pool of laid-off <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> workers before hiring people new to the company. Preparation of the plant site will begin later this month or early October, <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yoshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Arakawa </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> director, told a news conference in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> that <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s investment in the venture would be small by comparison to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s. `` Our basic responsibility is development so our investment is going to be rather small,'' <PERSON> Arakawa </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Arakawa </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> will take over the design and engineering of the new multi-purpose vehicle and supply parts provided by its manufacturing subsidiary, the <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> will assemble and provide most of the components of the new minivan About 75 percent of the components in the new vehicle will be made in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said. The venture would be the third formed by the two companies. In 1969, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> joined with <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automatic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transmission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sold its share to <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> in 1984 More recently, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> agreed to market versions of each other's utility vehicles in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> a year ago began assembly of two cars at a plant in <LOCATION> Flat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> owns 25 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>. The newest project, <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said, `` will give us an additional vehicle in a market niche that has grown from 5 percent -LRB- of the total truck market -RRB- in 1984 to 12 percent in 1987 and is projected at 18 -LRB- percent -RRB- to 19 percent for the 1993 model year.'' <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said only styling work has been completed so far on the new minivan, which is expected to be in production in the fall of 1991 for the 1992 model year. About 130,000 of the vehicles are expected to be produced annually, a relatively small number considering the size of the work force. The new minivan will be a more passenger-oriented vehicle than the minivan that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sells now _ the <ORGANIZATION> Aerostar </ORGANIZATION>, which has cargo and trailer-hauling capabilities. The Aerostar held 22 percent of the compact van market during the first eight months of this year. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> also produce minivans along with <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION>. But the imports hold just 4 percent of the minivan market. `` I think it's a great deal for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>,'' said auto analyst <PERSON> Maryann </PERSON> <PERSON> Keller </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Furman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Selz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mager </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deietz </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Birney </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has a marvelous way of working with Japanese partners to find products that are of mutual interest and mutual benefit to both parties. `` That's something <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has never been able to do ...'' she added. `` Chrysler is still struggling to find its way with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION>.''
