<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The directors of <ORGANIZATION> Morrison-Knudsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday elected <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Agee </PERSON> president in addition to his titles of chairman and chief executive officer. The company also announced the resignation of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Deasy </PERSON>, 51, who was the worldwide engineering, construction and shipbuilding company's chief executive officer until <PERSON> Agee </PERSON> took over last month. M-K said <PERSON> Deasy </PERSON>, who was corporate president, chief operating officer and a director, resigned effective immediately, `` to develop other business opportunities.'' <PERSON> Agee </PERSON> also announced other changes in senior management, which he said were aimed at strengthening management and streamlining operations control. M-K also started a new $ 45 million stock incentive plan for salaried employees. <PERSON> Agee </PERSON>, who had been on M-K's board of directors a total of 11 years, was elected chief executive last month after the company showed a large net loss in 1987 and also in the second quarter of this year. <PERSON> Agee </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> native, was chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Bendix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, when he led an ill-fated takeover battle that eventually saw him resign. One of the appointments announced Monday was a former <PERSON> Bendix </PERSON> and Allied Signal executive, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kayser </PERSON>, 57. <PERSON> Kayser </PERSON> is the new executive vice president, chief financial officer and a director. Under a new reporting structure approved by the board, the corporation's shipbuilding, mining and real estate development operations now will report directly to <PERSON> Agee </PERSON>. The real estate venture, <ORGANIZATION> EmKay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATI