<HEAD>Soybean Futures Expected To Drop On New Harvest Forecast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's new crop-production estimates, only slightly lower than predictions made a month ago, surprised many grain market analysts and should trigger a drop in corn and soybean futures prices, experts said Monday. Grain and soybean futures settled mixed Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in light trading ahead of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report. Soybeans were lower, wheat was higher and corn futures were mixed. On other markets, energy futures finished higher in a volatile session; precious metals were lower; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated slightly. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimated 1988 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn production at 4.46 billion bushels, compared with its August estimate of 4.48 billion bushels. The agency pegged the soybean crop at 1.47 bilion bushels, virtually unchanged from last month. And the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> predicted a wheat harvest of 1.81 billion bushels, compared with August's estimate of 1.82 billion. Although the numbers reflect severe drought damage and represent sharp reductions from last year's harvest _ 37 percent less corn, 23 percent fewer soybeans and 14 percent less wheat _ they were more optimistic than the market had anticipated and so were expected to exert downward pressure on prices, especially in soybeans and corn. `` I think corn will be down 3 to 4 cents, beans 10 cents or so, maybe even more,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Other traders said soybean futures prices could drop as much as 20 cents a bushel at Tuesday's opening. <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Leow </PERSON>, vice president of grain futures trading with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said spot-market sales of corn and soybeans linked to the advancing harvest already were weakening the futures markets. `` Between the numbers and the harvest, it probably means the market's not going higher in the short run,'' she said. `` We may just move sideways for a while. We wo n't go higher, we wo n't go lower, we'll trade in a range.'' For the wheat market, which has shown some vigor recently on expectations of rising export demand, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> report also had some bullish news. The government reduced its projection for 1988-89 Soviet grain production by 5 million metric tons to 205 million and raised its projected Soviet grain imports estimate to 27 million metric tons from 25 million. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> also reduced its projection for the Canadian wheat harvest by 2.6 million metric tons to 15.4 million. But <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON> said wheat prices still could decline Tuesday in sympathy with corn and soybeans. Wheat settled 1 cent to 2 \ cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 4.02 \ a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to -LCB- cent higher with September at $ 2.86 a bushel; oats were 2 cents lower to 3 cents higher with September at $ 2.61 a bushel; soybeans were 11 -LCB- cents lower to -LCB- cent higher with September at $ 8.70 -LCB- a Crude oil futures touched two-year lows below $ 14 a barrel on selling tied to the glut of oil caused by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> overproduction, then rallied late in the session to finish well above Friday's closing levels. <PERSON> Shahrokh </PERSON> <PERSON> Nikkah </PERSON>, vice president in charge of energy futures at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, attributed the dramatic turnaround on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> to two announcements from <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, a major <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> member. He said <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> asked its fellow members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> and also non-OPEC oil producers to show some restraint in their production. The Saudis also formally denied a rumor that they opposed calling a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s pricing committee to discuss the overproduction problem, he said. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 26 cents to 38 cents higher with October at $ 14.49 a barrel; heating oil was .56 cent to .81 cent higher with October at 41.68 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .56 cent to 1.10 cents higher with October at 42.62 cents a gallon. Precious metals futures finished slighty lower on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange but well above the day's lows Gold settled 30 cents to $ 1.60 lower with October at $ 422.80 a troy ounce; silver was .30 cent to 1.2 cents lower with September at $ 6.437 a troy ounce. Livestock and meat futures were narrowly mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .60 cent lower to .12 cent higher with October at 69.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .10 cent h