<HEAD>Son of Carl's Jr. Hamburger Founder Ordered to Pay $10,500</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Thomason and Bruns cq in final graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The son of the founder of the <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>'s Jr. hamburger chain was ordered Monday to repay $ 10,500 as part of a federal insider trading suit against him and 15 other relatives and company officers. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> was ordered to give up the amount he avoided in losses by acting on inside information to sell debt securities in <ORGANIZATION> Carl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Karcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in 1984. In ordering the penalty, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafeedie </PERSON> declined to impose treble damages, as had been requested by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which filed the insider-trading civil suit. The judge issued a permanent injunction barring <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> from future insider trades. The case continues against other defendants, including <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>'s Jr. founder <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>, his brother, and various of their spouses and children The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> case holds that <PERSON> Karchers </PERSON>, their in-laws and one non-family official of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> hamburger chain acted on confidential, advance notice of an unfavorable earnings report to sell securities and avoid potential losses in October 1984. They are accused of avoiding losses totaling $ 300,000, and treble damages could bring a total judgment against them to over $ 1 million. The attorney for <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> claimed that Monday's ruling represented a partial victory for his client, who maintained he did n't know he had broken any laws by selling <PERSON> Ka