<HEAD>Court Asked to Hold United Airlines in Contempt Over Pilot Hiring</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `In addition,' with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with United reax, fix typos; DELETES last graf pvs as outdated;
Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> asked a federal court Monday to hold <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in contempt for failing to hire enough blacks and women as pilots. In a motion filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, the commission charged that <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> has failed to abide by a 1976 consent decree in which the airline agreed to hire qualified minority and women pilots at double the rate at which they applied for the jobs in relation to white males. For example, according to <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> officials, if <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> had 100 qualified applicants for 10 jobs and 10 of the applicants were women or blacks, at least two of the 10 new people hired would have to be women or blacks under the consent decree. Based on data provided by the company, the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> received more than 32,500 applications for entry-level pilot positions between 1985 and 1987. Among the 1,400 pilots hired, 75 were blacks or other minorities and 59 were women _ a ratio smaller than the share of blacks and women in the pool of applicants, the commission said. The motion also alleges that <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> established a selection criteria that was not approved by the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> and then used some of the criteria selectively to benefit white males. `` We feel that some of the interviewing and evaluation standards were subjective and were applied subjectively,'' said <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the commission. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGA