<HEAD>General Mills Reports Record First-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it nearly quadrupled its first quarter net earnings compared with the same period last year, due largely to profits on the sale of its <ORGANIZATION> Talbots </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> clothing outlets. General <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> reported net income of $ 289.9 million, or $ 3.53 per share, in the three months ended Aug. 28, compared with net income of $ 77.2 million, or 87 cents per share, in the first quarter of 1987. The 1988 figures included a $ 199.1 million gain from discontinued operations. The sales of <ORGANIZATION> Talbots </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON>, completed during the first quarter, generated an after-tax profit of $ 220.6 million, the company said. The gain was reduced by establishment of a $ 21.5 million reserve for the disposition of the company's <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s cafeterias and other adjustments to previously discontinued operations. General <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> said it plans to dispose of <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s 100-unit chain during fiscal 1989. First-quarter sales rose 11 percent, to $ 1.38 billion from $ 1.24 billion, the company said. It attributed the sales increase largely to a more than 5 percent volume gain in consumer foods and expansion of restaurants by 69 company-operated units since the end of the first quarter of 1987. After-tax earnings from continuing operations rose to $ 90.8 million in the first quarter from first-quarter 1987 after-tax earnings of $ 80.9 million. Chairman H.B. <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> said much of the proceeds from the <ORGANIZATION> Talbots </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> sales was used to repurchase common stock, reducing average shares outstanding by 7 percent from a year earlier. First-quarter operating highlights reflect General <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>' aggressive internal expansion programs in consumer foods and restaurants Consumer foods reported gains of 9 percent in sales and 12.5 percent in operating profits in the first quarter of 1988. Restaurants reported gains of 15 percent in sales and 10 percent in operating profits over the first quarter of last year.
</TEXT>
