<HEAD>Dollar Opens Lower, Share Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar weakened in early trading Tuesday against the Japanese yen, while share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> rose moderately. On the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> foreign exchange market, the dollar opened at 133.23 yen, down from Monday's close of 133.42 yen. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency was weakening on increasing dollar-selling by investors, said <PERSON> Takamasa </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamazaki </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` A dollar-selling drive in the market has remained strong since last Tuesday, while investors have n't really been buying dollars,'' he said. The expected announcement Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for July was also prompting dollar-selling in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Yamazaki </PERSON> said. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose 136.52 points to 27,893.26 in the first 15 minutes of trading. The widely-followed market index rose 109.64 points Monday, closing at 27,756.74. A spokesman for the brokerage <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> characterized the mood on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as a `` good investment environment.'' `` The yen has been getting stronger, and apprehension about higher interest rates is fading. It's the best time to increase the market's energy,'' said <PERSON> Manjiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON>.
