<HEAD>Striking Workers Ratify Contract At Two Northwest Timber Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some 1,400 striking workers have ratified a four-year contract with <ORGANIZATION> DAW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> W-I </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, union officials announced Monday, in the latest of a series of agreements aimed at ending the multi-state timber strike. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Woodworkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America-U.S. </ORGANIZATION>, said a tentative contract approved last week was ratified Sunday by union members in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. About 400 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> also approved the agreement, according to union spokesman <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Witt </PERSON>. IWA business agent <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> in central Oregon said the two unions voted 3-1 in favor of the contract. The agreement matched one ratified Aug. 4 by workers at <ORGANIZATION> Willamette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hubbell </PERSON> said. That agreement provided for $ 1,400 bonuses during the first year of the contract, plus raises totaling 11 percent in the last three years. The strike, which began June 5, at its peak idled 9,000 workers at dozens of logging operations and lumber mills in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Only about 400 workers remain on strike, at <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Lakeview </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Lakeview </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hubbell </PERSON> said votes on a new contract with <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> were scheduled to be tallied Tuesday The company's 6,000 union workers were not affected by the walkout.
